# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: portsmouth
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] A nationwide census, known as **Census 2001**, was conducted in the United Kingdom on Sunday, 29 April 2001.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was the 20th UK census and recorded a resident population of 58,789,194.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The 2001 UK census was organised by the Office for National Statistics (ONS) in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Detailed results by region, council area, ward and output area are available from their respective websites.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Similar to previous UK censuses, the 2001 census was organised by the three statistical agencies, ONS, GROS, and NISRA, and coordinated at the national level by the Office for National Statistics.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Orders in Council to conduct the census, specifying the people and information to be included in the census, were made under the authority of the Census Act 1920 in Great Britain, and the Census Act (Northern Ireland) 1969 in Northern Ireland.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales these regulations were made by the Census Order 2000 (SI 744/2000), in Scotland by the Census (Scotland) Order 2000 (SSI 68/2000), and in Northern Ireland by the Census Order (Northern Ireland) 2000 (SRNI 168/2000).
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was administered through self-completion forms, in most cases delivered by enumerators to households and communal establishments in the three weeks before census night on 29 April.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time return by post was used as the main collection method, with enumerators following up in person where the forms were not returned.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The postal response rate was 88% in England and Wales, 91% in Scotland, and 92% in Northern Ireland.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] A total of 81,000 field staff were employed across the UK (70,000 in England and Wales, 8,000 in Scotland and 3,000 in Northern Ireland).
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was conducted at the height of the foot-and-mouth crisis, which led to extra precautions being adopted by the field staff, and suggestions that the census may have to be postponed.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, it was reported that the disease outbreak did not affect the effectiveness of the collection process.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The census was estimated to cost £259m over its 13-year cycle from the start of planning in 1993 to the delivery of final results in 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Printing of the 30 million census forms was subcontracted to Polestar Group, and processing of the returned census forms was subcontracted to Lockheed Martin in a contract worth £54m.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were initially scanned into digital format, then read with OMR and OCR, with manual entry where the automatic process could not read the forms.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The forms were then pulped and recycled, and the digital copies printed onto microfilm for storage and release after 100 years.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Once the data were returned to the statistics agencies it underwent further processing to ensure consistency and to impute missing values.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The overall response rate for the census, that is the proportion of the population who were included on a census form, was estimated to be 94% in England and Wales, 96.1% in Scotland and 95.2% in Northern Ireland.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was due to a number of factors: households with no response, households excluding residents from their returns, and addresses not included in the enumeration.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] In Manchester for example 25,000 people from 14,000 addresses were not enumerated because the address database was two years out of date.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The Local Authority with the lowest response was Kensington and Chelsea with 64%.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Hackney had the next lowest response at 72%.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Out of all local authorities, the ten lowest response rates were all in London.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results still represent 100 per cent of the population, however, because some individuals not completing their forms were instead identified by census enumerators, and through the use of cross-matching with a follow-up survey.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The results from the 2001 census were produced using a methodology known as the One Number Census.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] This was an attempt to adjust the census counts and impute answers to allow for estimated under-enumeration measured by the Census Coverage Survey (sample size 320,000 households), resulting in a single set of population estimates.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Although the 1851 census had included a question about religion on a separate response sheet, whose completion was not compulsory, the 2001 census was the first in Great Britain to ask about the religion of respondents on the main census form.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] An amendment to the 1920 Census Act (the Census (Amendment) Act 2000) was passed by Parliament to allow the question to be asked, and to allow the response to this question to be optional.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] The inclusion of the question enabled the Jedi census phenomenon to take place in the United Kingdom.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] In England and Wales 390,127 people stated their religion as Jedi, as did 14,052 people in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] 15% declared themselves of no religion (including Jedi at 0.7%, more than those who declared themselves as Sikh, Jewish or Buddhist) and 8% did not respond to the question.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Since the UK census relies on self-completion, the composition of the other ethnic group category is not fixed.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Analysis by the Office for National Statistics of the 220,000 people in England and Wales who ticked the other ethnic group box in the 2001 census reveals that 53 per cent were born in the Far East, 10 per cent in the UK, 10 per cent in the Middle East, and 7 per cent in Africa.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] People could write in an ethnic group under the 'other' heading.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] 26 per cent did not specify an ethnicity, but of the remainder 23 per cent wrote Filipino, 21 per cent Japanese, 11 per cent Vietnamese, 11 per cent Arab, 6 per cent Middle Eastern and 4 per cent North African.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic groups began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for English respondents.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of an English tick-box, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] However, if 'English' was written in under the "any other white background" it was not clear whether it would be counted as an ethnic group in same the way as the Welsh.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Following criticism, English was included as a tick-box option in the 2011 census.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] It is sometimes claimed that the 2001 census revealed that two-thirds of the population of Wales described themselves as of Welsh nationality.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] In fact, the 2001 census did not collect any information on nationality.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Controversy surrounding the classification of ethnic group began as early as 2000, when it was revealed that respondents in Scotland and Northern Ireland would be able to check a box describing themselves as Scottish or Irish, an option not available for Welsh respondents.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Prior to the census, *Plaid Cymru* backed a petition calling for the inclusion of a Welsh tickbox and for the National Assembly for Wales to have primary law-making powers and its own National Statistics Office.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] With an absence of a Welsh tickbox, the only other tickbox available was "white-British", "Irish", or "other".
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] For the first time in a UK census, those wishing to describe their ethnicity as Cornish were given their own code number (06) on the 2001 UK census form, alongside those for people wishing to describe themselves as English, Welsh, Irish or Scottish.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] About 34,000 people in Cornwall and 3,500 people in the rest of the UK wrote on their census forms in 2001 that they considered their ethnic group to be Cornish.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] This represented nearly 7% of the population of Cornwall.
[src:portsmouth/2001-united-kingdom-census] Various Cornish organisations were campaigning for the inclusion of the Cornish tick box on the next census in 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2003-world-aquatics-championships] The **10th FINA World Aquatics Championships** were held July 12–27, 2003 in Barcelona, Spain.
[src:portsmouth/2003-world-aquatics-championships] The championships featured competition in all 5 of FINA's disciplines: Swimming, Diving, Synchronised swimming, Water Polo, and Open Water Swimming.
[src:portsmouth/2003-world-aquatics-championships] Competition was held in the facilities all around the city: Palau Sant Jordi, Piscines Bernat Picornell, Piscina Municipal de Montjuïc, Club de Natació de Barcelona and Port Vell.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A major worldwide financial crisis centered in the United States took place in 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The causes included excessive speculation on property values by both homeowners and financial institutions, leading to the 2000s United States housing bubble.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was exacerbated by predatory lending for subprime mortgages and by deficiencies in regulation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Cash out refinancings had fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The first phase of the crisis was the subprime mortgage crisis, which began in early 2007, as mortgage-backed securities (MBS) tied to U.S. real estate, and a vast web of derivatives linked to those MBS collapsed in value.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A liquidity crisis spread to global institutions by mid-2007 and climaxed with the bankruptcy of Lehman Brothers in September 2008, which triggered a stock market crash and bank runs in several countries.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in late-2007, as well as the United States bear market of 2007–2009.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was also a contributor to the 2008–2011 Icelandic financial crisis and the euro area crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As the Federal Reserve ("Fed") lowered the federal funds rate from 2000 to 2003, institutions increasingly targeted low-income homebuyers, largely belonging to racial minorities, with high-risk loans; this development went unattended by regulators.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As interest rates rose from 2004 to 2006, the cost of mortgages rose and the demand for housing fell; in early 2007, as more U.S. subprime mortgage holders began defaulting on their repayments, lenders went bankrupt, culminating in the bankruptcy of New Century Financial in April.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] As demand and prices continued to fall, the financial contagion spread to global credit markets by August 2007, and central banks began injecting liquidity.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In March 2008, Bear Stearns, the fifth-largest U.S. investment bank, was sold to JPMorgan Chase in a "fire sale" backed by Fed financing.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In response to the growing crisis, governments around the world deployed massive bailouts of financial institutions and used monetary policy and fiscal policies to prevent an economic collapse of the global financial system.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] By July 2008, Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, companies which together owned or guaranteed half of the U.S. housing market, verged on collapse; the Housing and Economic Recovery Act of 2008 enabled the federal government to seize them on September 7.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] On October 3, Congress passed the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, authorizing the Treasury Department to purchase toxic assets and bank stocks through the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program (TARP).
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Fed began a program of quantitative easing by buying treasury bonds and other assets, such as MBS, and the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, signed in February 2009 by newly elected president Barack Obama, included a range of measures intended to preserve existing jobs and create new ones.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] These initiatives combined, coupled with actions taken in other countries, ended the worst of the Great Recession by mid-2009.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Assessments of the crisis's impact in the U.S. vary, but suggest that some 8.7 million jobs were lost, causing unemployment to rise from 5% in 2007 to a high of 10% in October 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The percentage of citizens living in poverty rose from 12.5% in 2007 to 15.1% in 2010.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by 53% between October 2007 and March 2009, and some estimates suggest that one in four households lost 75% or more of their net worth.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was passed, overhauling financial regulations.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was opposed by many Republicans, and it was weakened by the Economic Growth, Regulatory Relief, and Consumer Protection Act in 2018.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were also adopted by countries around the world.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis exacerbated the Great Recession, a global recession that began in mid-2007.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] It was among the five worst financial crises the world had experienced and led to a loss of more than $2 trillion from the global economy.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 (~$15 trillion in 2024) trillion.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The increase in cash out refinancings, as home values rose, fueled an increase in consumption that could no longer be sustained when home prices declined.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many financial institutions owned investments whose value was based on home mortgages such as mortgage-backed securities, or credit derivatives used to insure them against failure, which declined in value significantly.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The International Monetary Fund estimated that large U.S. and European banks lost more than $1 trillion on toxic assets and from bad loans from January 2007 to September 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Lack of investor confidence in bank solvency and declines in credit availability led to plummeting stock and commodity prices in late 2008 and early 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The crisis rapidly spread into a global economic shock, resulting in several bank failures.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Economies worldwide slowed during this period since credit tightened and international trade declined.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Housing markets suffered and unemployment soared, resulting in evictions and foreclosures.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] From its peak in the second quarter of 2007 at $61.4 trillion, household wealth in the United States fell $11 trillion, to $50.4 trillion by the end of the first quarter of 2009, resulting in a decline in consumption, then a decline in business investment.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the fourth quarter of 2008, the quarter-over-quarter decline in real GDP in the U.S. was 8.4%.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The U.S. unemployment rate peaked at 11.0% in October 2009, the highest rate since 1983 and roughly twice the pre-crisis rate.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The average hours per work week declined to 33, the lowest level since the government began collecting the data in 1964.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The economic crisis started in the U.S. but spread to the rest of the world.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] U.S. consumption accounted for more than a third of the growth in global consumption between 2000 and 2007 and the rest of the world depended on the U.S. consumer as a source of demand.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Toxic securities were owned by corporate and institutional investors globally.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Derivatives such as credit default swaps also increased the linkage between large financial institutions.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The de-leveraging of financial institutions, as assets were sold to pay back obligations that could not be refinanced in frozen credit markets, further accelerated the solvency crisis and caused a decrease in international trade.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Reductions in the growth rates of developing countries were due to falls in trade, commodity prices, investment and remittances sent from migrant workers (example: Armenia).
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] States with fragile political systems feared that investors from Western states would withdraw their money because of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In effect, the central banks went from being the "lender of last resort" to the "lender of only resort" for a significant portion of the economy.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In some cases the Fed was considered the "buyer of last resort".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] During the fourth quarter of 2008, these central banks purchased US$2.5 trillion (~$3.57 trillion in 2024) of government debt and troubled private assets from banks.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This was the largest liquidity injection into the credit market, and the largest monetary policy action in world history.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve created then-significant amounts of new currency as a method to combat the liquidity trap.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Bailouts came in the form of trillions of dollars of loans, asset purchases, guarantees, and direct spending.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Significant controversy accompanied the bailouts, such as in the case of the AIG bonus payments controversy, leading to the development of a variety of "decision making frameworks", to help balance competing policy interests during times of financial crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Alistair Darling, the U.K.'s Chancellor of the Exchequer at the time of the crisis, stated in 2018 that Britain came within hours of "a breakdown of law and order" the day that Royal Bank of Scotland was bailed-out.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Instead of financing more domestic loans, some banks instead spent some of the stimulus money in more profitable areas such as investing in emerging markets and foreign currencies.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In July 2010, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act was enacted in the United States to "promote the financial stability of the United States".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Basel III capital and liquidity standards were adopted worldwide.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Since the 2008 financial crisis, consumer regulators in America have more closely supervised sellers of credit cards and home mortgages in order to deter anticompetitive practices that led to the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] At least two major reports on the causes of the crisis were produced by the U.S.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Congress: the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission report, released January 2011, and a report by the United States Senate Homeland Security Permanent Subcommittee on Investigations entitled Wall Street and the Financial Crisis: Anatomy of a Financial Collapse, released April 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In total, 47 bankers served jail time as a result of the crisis, over half of whom were from Iceland, where the crisis was the most severe and led to the collapse of all three major Icelandic banks.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In April 2012, Geir Haarde of Iceland became the only politician to be convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the aftermath of the crisis, U.S. authorities intensified enforcement actions against financial misconduct, including high-profile insider trading prosecutions such as that of Raj Rajaratnam, who was convicted in 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Only one banker in the United States served jail time as a result of the crisis, Kareem Serageldin, a banker at Credit Suisse who was sentenced to 30 months in jail and returned $24.6 million in compensation for manipulating bond prices to hide $1 billion of losses.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] No individuals in the United Kingdom were convicted as a result of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Goldman Sachs*, Goldman Sachs paid a $550 million civil penalty and acknowledged that its marketing materials for CDO contained incomplete information, settling securities fraud charges after allegedly anticipating the financial crisis and selling toxic investments to its clients.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] With fewer resources to risk in creative destruction, the number of patent applications was flat, compared to exponential increases in patent application in prior years.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Typical American families did not fare well, nor did the "wealthy-but-not-wealthiest" families just beneath the pyramid's top.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, half of the poorest families in the United States did not have wealth declines at all during the crisis because they generally did not own financial investments whose value could fluctuate.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve surveyed 4,000 households from 2007 to 2009, and found that the total wealth of 63% of all Americans declined in that period and 77% of the richest families had a decrease in total wealth, while only 50% of those on the bottom of the pyramid suffered a decrease.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The following is a timeline of the major events of the financial crisis, including government responses, and the subsequent economic recovery.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In the table, the names of emerging and developing economies are shown in boldface type, while the names of developed economies are in Roman (regular) type.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The expansion of central bank lending in response to the crisis was not confined to the Federal Reserve's provision of aid to individual financial institutions.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve has also conducted several innovative lending programs to improve liquidity and strengthen different financial institutions and markets, such as Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] In this case, the major problem in the market is the lack of free cash reserves and flows to secure the loans.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The Federal Reserve took many steps to deal with financial market liquidity worries.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] One of these steps was a credit line for major traders, who act as the Fed's partners in open market activities.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, loan programs were set up to make the money market mutual funds and commercial paper market more flexible.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Term Asset-Backed Securities Loan Facility (TALF) was put in place thanks to a joint effort with the US Department of the Treasury.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This plan made it easier for consumers and businesses to get credit by giving Americans who owned high-quality asset-backed securities more credit.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Before the crisis, the Federal Reserve's stocks of Treasury securities were sold to pay for the increase in credit.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This method was meant to keep banks from trying to give out their extra savings, which could cause the federal funds rate to drop below where it was supposed to be.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] However, in October 2008, the Federal Reserve was granted the power to provide banks with interest payments on their surplus reserves.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] This created a motivation for banks to retain their reserves instead of disbursing them, thus reducing the need for the Federal Reserve to hedge its increased lending by decreases in alternative assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Money market funds also went through runs when people lost faith in the market.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] To keep it from getting worse, the Fed said it would give money to mutual fund companies.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Also, the Department of Treasury said that it would briefly cover the assets of the fund.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Both of these things helped get the fund market back to normal, which helped the commercial paper market, which most businesses use to run.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] The FDIC also did several things, such as raising the insurance cap from $100,000 to $250,000, to boost customer trust.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] They engaged in quantitative easing, which added more than $4 trillion to the financial system and got banks to start lending again, both to each other and to people.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] Many homeowners who were trying to keep their homes from going into default got housing credits.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p01] A package of policies was passed that let borrowers refinance their loans even though the value of their homes was less than what they still owed on their mortgages.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The relaxing of credit lending standards by investment banks and commercial banks allowed for a significant increase in subprime lending.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime had not become less risky; Wall Street just accepted this higher risk.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Due to competition between mortgage lenders for revenue and market share, and when the supply of creditworthy borrowers was limited, mortgage lenders relaxed underwriting standards and originated riskier mortgages to less creditworthy borrowers.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the view of some analysts, the relatively conservative government-sponsored enterprises (GSEs) policed mortgage originators and maintained relatively high underwriting standards prior to 2003.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] However, as market power shifted from securitizers to originators, and as intense competition from private securitizers undermined GSE power, mortgage standards declined and risky loans proliferated.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The riskiest loans were originated in 2004–2007, the years of the most intense competition between securitizers and the lowest market share for the GSEs.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The GSEs eventually relaxed their standards to try to catch up with the private banks.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Depending on how "subprime" mortgages are defined, they remained below 10% of all mortgage originations until 2004, when they rose to nearly 20% and remained there through the 2005–2006 peak of the United States housing bubble.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Although they concede that governmental policies had some role in causing the crisis, they contend that GSE loans performed better than loans securitized by private investment banks, and performed better than some loans originated by institutions that held loans in their own portfolios.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In his dissent to the majority report of the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, conservative American Enterprise Institute fellow Peter J.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Based upon information in the SEC's December 2011 securities fraud case against six former executives of Fannie and Freddie, Peter Wallison and Edward Pinto estimated that, in 2008, Fannie and Freddie held 13 million substandard loans totaling over $2 trillion.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In the early and mid-2000s, the Bush administration called numerous times for investigations into the safety and soundness of the GSEs and their swelling portfolio of subprime mortgages.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The hearings never resulted in new legislation or formal investigation of Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, as many of the committee members refused to accept the report and instead rebuked OFHEO for their attempt at regulation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Some, such as Wallison, believe this was an early warning to the systemic risk that the growing market in subprime mortgages posed to the U.S. financial system that went unheeded.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Sub-prime loans made by CRA-covered institutions constituted a 3% market share of LMI loans in 1998, but in the run-up to the crisis, fully 25% of all subprime lending occurred at CRA-covered institutions and another 25% of subprime loans had some connection with CRA.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] To other analysts the delay between CRA rule changes in 1995 and the explosion of subprime lending is not surprising, and does not exonerate the CRA.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They contend that there were two, connected causes to the crisis: the relaxation of underwriting standards in 1995 and the ultra-low interest rates initiated by the Federal Reserve after the terrorist attack on September 11, 2001.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Both causes had to be in place before the crisis could take place.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Critics also point out that publicly announced CRA loan commitments were massive, totaling $4.5 trillion in the years between 1994 and 2007.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] They also argue that the Federal Reserve's classification of CRA loans as "prime" is based on the faulty and self-serving assumption that high-interest-rate loans (3 percentage points over average) equal "subprime" loans.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Others have pointed out that there were not enough of these loans made to cause a crisis of this magnitude.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By March 2011, the FDIC had paid out $9 billion (c. $12.3 billion in 2024) to cover losses on bad loans at 165 failed financial institutions.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Congressional Budget Office estimated, in June 2011, that the bailout to Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac exceeds $300 billion (c. $411 billion in 2024) (calculated by adding the fair value deficits of the entities to the direct bailout funds at the time).
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other words, bubbles in both markets developed even though only the residential market was affected by these potential causes.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] *residential housing* bubble (as opposed to other types of bubbles) led to financial crisis was that it was supported by a huge number of substandard loans—generally with low or no downpayments.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Krugman's contention (that the growth of a commercial real estate bubble indicates that U.S. housing policy was not the cause of the crisis) is challenged by additional analysis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After researching the default of commercial loans during the financial crisis, Xudong An and Anthony B.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Business journalist Kimberly Amadeo reported: "The first signs of decline in residential real estate occurred in 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Three years later, commercial real estate started feeling the effects." Denice A.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Between 1998 and 2006, the price of the typical American house increased by 124%.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During the 1980s and 1990s, the national median home price ranged from 2.9 to 3.1 times median household income.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By contrast, this ratio increased to 4.0 in 2004, and 4.6 in 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This housing bubble resulted in many homeowners refinancing their homes at lower interest rates, or financing consumer spending by taking out second mortgages secured by the price appreciation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In a Peabody Award-winning program, NPR correspondents argued that a "Giant Pool of Money" (represented by $70 trillion in worldwide fixed income investments) sought higher yields than those offered by U.S.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This pool of money had roughly doubled in size from 2000 to 2007, yet the supply of relatively safe, income generating investments had not grown as fast.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Investment banks on Wall Street answered this demand with products such as the mortgage-backed security and the collateralized debt obligation that were assigned safe ratings by the credit rating agencies.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In effect, Wall Street connected this pool of money to the mortgage market in the US, with enormous fees accruing to those throughout the mortgage supply chain, from the mortgage broker selling the loans to small banks that funded the brokers and the large investment banks behind them.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By approximately 2003, the supply of mortgages originated at traditional lending standards had been exhausted, and continued strong demand began to drive down lending standards.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The collateralized debt obligation in particular enabled financial institutions to obtain investor funds to finance subprime and other lending, extending or increasing the housing bubble and generating large fees.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This essentially places cash payments from multiple mortgages or other debt obligations into a single pool from which specific securities draw in a specific sequence of priority.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Those securities first in line received investment-grade ratings from rating agencies.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Securities with lower priority had lower credit ratings but theoretically a higher rate of return on the amount invested.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2008, average U.S. housing prices had declined by over 20% from their mid-2006 peak.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As prices declined, borrowers with adjustable-rate mortgages could not refinance to avoid the higher payments associated with rising interest rates and began to default.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] During 2007, lenders began foreclosure proceedings on nearly 1.3 million properties, a 79% increase over 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased to 2.3 million in 2008, an 81% increase vs.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By August 2008, approximately 9% of all U.S. mortgages outstanding were either delinquent or in foreclosure.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By September 2009, this had risen to 14.4%.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] After the bubble burst, Australian economist John Quiggin wrote: "And, unlike the Great Depression, this crisis was entirely the product of financial markets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Lower interest rates encouraged borrowing.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] From 2000 to 2003, the Federal Reserve lowered the federal funds rate target from 6.5% to 1.0%.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This was done to soften the effects of the collapse of the dot-com bubble and the September 11 attacks, as well as to combat a perceived risk of deflation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] As early as 2002, it was apparent that credit was fueling housing instead of business investment as some economists went so far as to advocate that the Fed "needs to create a housing bubble to replace the Nasdaq bubble".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, empirical studies using data from advanced countries show that excessive credit growth contributed greatly to the severity of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Additional downward pressure on interest rates was created by a growing U.S. current account deficit, which peaked along with the housing bubble in 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke explained how trade deficits required the U.S. to borrow money from abroad, in the process bidding up bond prices and lowering interest rates.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bernanke explained that between 1996 and 2004, the U.S. current account deficit increased by $650 billion, from 1.5% to 5.8% of GDP.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financing these deficits required the country to borrow large sums from abroad, much of it from countries running trade surpluses.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] These were mainly the emerging economies in Asia and oil-exporting nations.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The balance of payments identity requires that a country (such as the US) running a current account deficit also have a capital account (investment) surplus of the same amount.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Hence large and growing amounts of foreign funds (capital) flowed into the U.S. to finance its imports.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] All of this created demand for various types of financial assets, raising the prices of those assets while lowering interest rates.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign investors had these funds to lend either because they had very high personal savings rates (as high as 40% in China) or because of high oil prices.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Ben Bernanke referred to this as a "saving glut".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A flood of funds (capital or liquidity) reached the U.S. financial markets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Foreign governments supplied funds by purchasing Treasury bonds and thus avoided much of the direct effect of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households used funds borrowed from foreigners to finance consumption or to bid up the prices of housing and financial assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Financial institutions invested foreign funds in mortgage-backed securities.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The Fed then raised the Fed funds rate significantly between July 2004 and July 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This contributed to an increase in one-year and five-year adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) rates, making ARM interest rate resets more expensive for homeowners.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This may have also contributed to the deflation of the housing bubble, as asset prices generally move inversely to interest rates.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] It became riskier to speculate in housing.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. housing and financial assets dramatically declined in value after the housing bubble burst.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Subprime lending standards declined in the U.S.: in early 2000, a subprime borrower had a FICO score of 660 or less.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] By 2005, many lenders dropped the required FICO score to 620, making it much easier to qualify for prime loans and making subprime lending a riskier business.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Proof of income and assets were de-emphasized.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Loans at first required full documentation, then low documentation, then no documentation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] One subprime mortgage product that gained wide acceptance was the no income, no job, no asset verification required (NINJA) mortgage.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Informally, these loans were aptly referred to as "liar loans" because they encouraged borrowers to be less than honest in the loan application process.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Testimony given to the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission by whistleblower Richard M.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Bowen III on events during his tenure as the Business Chief Underwriter for Correspondent Lending in the Consumer Lending Group for Citigroup, where he was responsible for over 220 professional underwriters, suggests that by 2006 and 2007, the collapse of mortgage underwriting standards was endemic.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] His testimony stated that by 2006, 60% of mortgages purchased by Citigroup from some 1,600 mortgage companies were "defective" (were not underwritten to policy, or did not contain all policy-required documents).
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This, despite the fact that each of these 1,600 originators was contractually responsible (certified via representations and warrantees) that its mortgage originations met Citigroup standards.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Moreover, during 2007, "defective mortgages (from mortgage originators contractually bound to perform underwriting to Citi's standards) increased to over 80% of production".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] The analysis, conducted on behalf of 23 investment and commercial banks, including 7 "too big to fail" banks, additionally showed that 28% of the sampled loans did not meet the minimal standards of any issuer.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Clayton's analysis further showed that 39% of these loans (i.e. those not meeting *any* issuer's minimal underwriting standards) were subsequently securitized and sold to investors.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Predatory lending refers to the practice of unscrupulous lenders enticing borrowers to enter into unfair or abusive secured loans for inappropriate purposes.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In May 2009, Bank of America modified 64,000 Countrywide loans as a result.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] When housing prices decreased, homeowners in ARMs then had little incentive to pay their monthly payments, since their home equity had disappeared.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This caused Countrywide's financial condition to deteriorate, ultimately resulting in a decision by the Office of Thrift Supervision to seize the lender.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Former employees from Ameriquest, which was the United States' leading wholesale lender, described a system in which they were pushed to falsify mortgage documents and then sell the mortgages to Wall Street banks eager to make fast profits.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] There is growing evidence that such mortgage frauds may be a cause of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] According to Barry Eichengreen, the roots of the financial crisis lay in the deregulation of financial markets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] A 2012 OECD study suggested that bank regulation based on the Basel accords encouraged unconventional business practices and contributed to or reinforced the financial crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] In other cases, laws were changed or enforcement weakened in parts of the financial system.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Prior to the crisis, financial institutions became highly leveraged, increasing their appetite for risky investments and reducing their resilience in case of losses.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Much of this leverage was achieved using complex financial instruments such as off-balance sheet securitization and derivatives, which made it difficult for creditors and regulators to monitor and try to reduce financial institution risk levels.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. households and financial institutions became increasingly indebted or overleveraged during the years preceding the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] This increased their vulnerability to the collapse of the housing bubble and worsened the ensuing economic downturn.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] Free cash used by consumers from home equity extraction doubled from $627 billion in 2001 to $1,428 billion in 2005 as the housing bubble built, a total of nearly $5 trillion over the period, contributing to economic growth worldwide.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p02] U.S. home mortgage debt relative to GDP increased from an average of 46% during the 1990s to 73% during 2008, reaching $10.5 trillion (c. $15 trillion in 2024).
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. household debt as a percentage of annual disposable personal income was 127% at the end of 2007, versus 77% in 1990.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1981, U.S. private debt was 123% of GDP; by the third quarter of 2008, it was 290%.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From 2004 to 2007, the top five U.S. investment banks each significantly increased their financial leverage, which increased their vulnerability to a financial shock.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Changes in capital requirements, intended to keep U.S. banks competitive with their European counterparts, allowed lower *risk weightings* for AAA-rated securities.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The shift from first-loss tranches to AAA-rated tranches was seen by regulators as a risk reduction that compensated the higher leverage.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These five institutions reported over $4.1 trillion in debt for fiscal year 2007, about 30% of U.S. nominal GDP for 2007.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Lehman Brothers went bankrupt and was liquidated, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold at fire-sale prices, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley became commercial banks, subjecting themselves to more stringent regulation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With the exception of Lehman, these companies required or received government support.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac, two U.S. government-sponsored enterprises, owned or guaranteed nearly $5 trillion (c. $7.13 trillion in 2024) trillion in mortgage obligations at the time they were placed into conservatorship by the U.S. government in September 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These seven entities were highly leveraged and had $9 trillion in debt or guarantee obligations; yet they were not subject to the same regulation as depository banks.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Behavior that may be optimal for an individual, such as saving more during adverse economic conditions, can be detrimental if too many individuals pursue the same behavior, as ultimately one person's consumption is another person's income.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Too many consumers attempting to save or pay down debt simultaneously is called the paradox of thrift and can cause or deepen a recession.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Hyman Minsky also described a "paradox of deleveraging" as financial institutions that have too much leverage (debt relative to equity) cannot all de-leverage simultaneously without significant declines in the value of their assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The term financial innovation refers to the ongoing development of financial products designed to achieve particular client objectives, such as offsetting a particular risk exposure (such as the default of a borrower) or to assist with obtaining financing.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The usage of these products expanded dramatically in the years leading up to the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These products vary in complexity and the ease with which they can be valued on the books of financial institutions.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] CDO issuance grew from an estimated $20 billion in Q1 2004 to its peak of over $180 billion by Q1 2007, then declined back under $20 billion by Q1 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, the credit quality of CDO's declined from 2000 to 2007, as the level of subprime and other non-prime mortgage debt increased from 5% to 36% of CDO assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As described in the section on subprime lending, the CDS and portfolio of CDS called synthetic CDO enabled a theoretically infinite amount to be wagered on the finite value of housing loans outstanding, provided that buyers and sellers of the derivatives could be found.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, buying a CDS to insure a CDO ended up giving the seller the same risk as if they owned the CDO, when those CDO's became worthless.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This boom in innovative financial products went hand in hand with more complexity.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] It multiplied the number of actors connected to a single mortgage (including mortgage brokers, specialized originators, the securitizers and their due diligence firms, managing agents and trading desks, and finally investors, insurances and providers of repo funding).
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Instead of spreading risk this provided the ground for fraudulent acts, misjudgments and finally market collapse.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists have studied the crisis as an instance of cascades in financial networks, where institutions' instability destabilized other institutions and led to knock-on effects.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Mortgage risks were underestimated by almost all institutions in the chain from originator to investor by underweighting the possibility of falling housing prices based on historical trends of the past 50 years.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While financial derivatives and structured products helped partition and shift risk between financial participants, it was the underestimation of falling housing prices and the resultant losses that led to aggregate risk.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For a variety of reasons, market participants did not accurately measure the risk inherent with financial innovation such as MBS and CDOs or understand its effect on the overall stability of the financial system.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The pricing model for CDOs clearly did not reflect the level of risk they introduced into the system.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] AIG insured obligations of various financial institutions through the usage of credit default swaps.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The basic CDS transaction involved AIG receiving a premium in exchange for a promise to pay money to party A in the event party B defaulted.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] However, AIG did not have the financial strength to support its many CDS commitments as the crisis progressed and was taken over by the government in September 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] U.S. taxpayers provided over $180 billion in government loans and investments in AIG during 2008 and early 2009, through which the money flowed to various counterparties to CDS transactions, including many large global financial institutions.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission (FCIC) made the major government study of the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The limitations of a widely used financial model also were not properly understood.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This formula assumed that the price of CDS was correlated with and could predict the correct price of mortgage-backed securities.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Because it was highly tractable, it rapidly came to be used by a huge percentage of CDO and CDS investors, issuers, and rating agencies.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As financial assets became more complex and harder to value, investors were reassured by the fact that the international bond rating agencies and bank regulators accepted as valid some complex mathematical models that showed the risks were much smaller than they actually were.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] George Soros commented that "The super-boom got out of hand when the new products became so complicated that the authorities could no longer calculate the risks and started relying on the risk management methods of the banks themselves.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Similarly, the rating agencies relied on the information provided by the originators of synthetic products.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A conflict of interest between investment management professional and institutional investors, combined with a global glut in investment capital, led to bad investments by asset managers in over-priced credit assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Professional investment managers generally are compensated based on the volume of client assets under management.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is, therefore, an incentive for asset managers to expand their assets under management in order to maximize their compensation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As the glut in global investment capital caused the yields on credit assets to decline, asset managers were faced with the choice of either investing in assets where returns did not reflect true credit risk or returning funds to clients.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Many asset managers continued to invest client funds in over-priced (under-yielding) investments, to the detriment of their clients, so they could maintain their assets under management.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] They supported this choice with a "plausible deniability" of the risks associated with subprime-based credit assets because the loss experience with early "vintages" of subprime loans was so low.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the dominance of the above formula, there are documented attempts of the financial industry, occurring before the crisis, to address the formula limitations, specifically the lack of dependence dynamics and the poor representation of extreme events.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The volume *Credit Correlation: Life After Copulas*, published in 2007 by World Scientific, summarizes a 2006 conference held by Merrill Lynch in London where several practitioners attempted to propose models rectifying some of the copula limitations.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] See also the article by Donnelly and Embrechts and the book by Brigo, Pallavicini and Torresetti, that reports relevant warnings and research on CDOs appeared in 2006.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There is strong evidence that the riskiest, worst performing mortgages were funded through the "shadow banking system" and that competition from the shadow banking system may have pressured more traditional institutions to lower their underwriting standards and originate riskier loans.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These entities became critical to the credit markets underpinning the financial system, but were not subject to the same regulatory controls.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Further, these entities were vulnerable because of asset–liability mismatch, meaning that they borrowed short-term in liquid markets to purchase long-term, illiquid and risky assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that disruptions in credit markets would force them to engage in rapid deleveraging, selling their long-term assets at depressed prices.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economist Paul Krugman, laureate of the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences, described the run on the shadow banking system as the "core of what happened" to cause the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He referred to this lack of controls as "malign neglect" and argued that regulation should have been imposed on all banking-like activity.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Without the ability to obtain investor funds in exchange for most types of mortgage-backed securities or asset-backed commercial paper, investment banks and other entities in the shadow banking system could not provide funds to mortgage firms and other corporations.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This meant that nearly one-third of the U.S. lending mechanism was frozen and continued to be frozen into June 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While traditional banks raised their lending standards, it was the collapse of the shadow banking system that was the primary cause of the reduction in funds available for borrowing.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Caballero, Emmanuel Farhi, and Pierre-Olivier Gourinchas argued that the financial crisis was attributable to "global asset scarcity, which led to large capital flows toward the United States and to the creation of asset bubbles that eventually burst".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Long-only commodity index funds became popular – by one estimate investment increased from $90 billion in 2006 to $200 billion at the end of 2007, while commodity prices increased 71% – which raised concern as to whether these index funds caused the commodity bubble.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cause of the global asset bubble can be partially attributable to the global savings glut.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As theorized by Andrew Metrick, the demand for safe assets following the Asian Financial Crisis coupled with the lack of circulating treasuries created an unmet demand for "risk free" assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Thus, institutional investors like sovereign wealth funds and pension funds began purchasing synthetic safe assets like Triple-A Mortgage Backed Securities.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As a consequence, the demand for so-called safe assets fueled the free flow of capital into housing in the United States.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This greatly worsened the crisis as banks and other financial institutions were incentivized to issue more mortgages than before.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Some commentators and economists associated with the Austrian School of economics, including former U.S.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Congressman Ron Paul and historian Tom Woods, have offered a libertarian interpretation of the crisis which differs from the explanations centered on deregulation and government oversight.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Ron Paul's book, *End the Fed,* Paul argues that the Federal Reserve's prolonged policy of artificially low interest rates in the early 2000s created a credit bubble that allowed for speculative investments and unsustainable levels of debt, particularly in housing.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In Tom Woods' book *Meltdown*, he also contends that Federal Reserve manipulation of the money supply and credit markets distorted normal price signals, leading to widespread malinvestment, resulting in an inevitable correction.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Paul and Woods also criticized Fannie Mae's and Freddie Mac's role in the crisis, asserting that the entities engaged in excessive risk-taking by expanding homeownership beyond sustainable levels.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In doing this, the government intervention created moral hazard by assuring large financial institutions that they would receive government support in times of crisis, which Paul and Woods believe encouraged riskier behavior.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 1998 book, John McMurtry suggested that a financial crisis is a systemic crisis of capitalism itself.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his 1978 book, *The Downfall of Capitalism and Communism*, Ravi Batra suggests that growing inequality of financial capitalism produces speculative bubbles that burst and result in depression and major political changes.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also suggested that a "demand gap" related to differing wage and productivity growth explains deficit and debt dynamics important to stock market developments.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] John Bellamy Foster, a political economy analyst and editor of the *Monthly Review*, believed that the decrease in GDP growth rates since the early 1970s is due to increasing market saturation.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Marxian economics followers Andrew Kliman, Michael Roberts, and Guglielmo Carchedi, in contradistinction to the *Monthly Review* school represented by Foster, pointed to capitalism's long-term tendency of the rate of profit to fall as the underlying cause of crises generally.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From this point of view, the problem was the inability of capital to grow or accumulate at sufficient rates through productive investment alone.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Low rates of profit in productive sectors led to speculative investment in riskier assets, where there was potential for greater return on investment.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The speculative frenzy of the late 1990s and 2000s was, in this view, a consequence of a rising organic composition of capital, expressed through the fall in the rate of profit.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to Michael Roberts, the fall in the rate of profit "eventually triggered the credit crunch of 2007 when credit could no longer support profits".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005 book, *The Battle for the Soul of Capitalism*, John C.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Bogle wrote that "Corporate America went astray largely because the power of managers went virtually unchecked by our gatekeepers for far too long".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In his book *The Big Mo*, Mark Roeder, a former executive at the Swiss-based UBS Bank, suggested that large-scale momentum, or The Big Mo, "played a pivotal role" in the financial crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Roeder suggested that "recent technological advances, such as computer-driven trading programs, together with the increasingly interconnected nature of markets, has magnified the momentum effect.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Robert Reich attributed the economic downturn to the stagnation of wages in the United States, particularly those of the hourly workers who comprise 80% of the workforce.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This stagnation forced the population to borrow to meet the cost of living.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists Ailsa McKay and Margunn Bjørnholt argued that the financial crisis and the response to it revealed a crisis of ideas in mainstream economics and within the economics profession, and call for a reshaping of both the economy, economic theory and the economics profession.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A report by the International Labour Organization concluded that cooperative banking institutions were less likely to fail than their competitors during the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The cooperative banking sector had 20% market share of the European banking sector, but accounted for only 7% of all the write-downs and losses between the third quarter of 2007 and first quarter of 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2008, in the U.S., the rate of commercial bank failures was almost triple that of credit unions, and almost five times the credit union rate in 2010.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Credit unions increased their lending to small- and medium-sized businesses while overall lending to those businesses decreased.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Economists, particularly followers of mainstream economics, mostly failed to predict the crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several followers of heterodox economics predicted the crisis, with varying arguments.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dirk Bezemer credits 12 economists with predicting the crisis: Dean Baker, Wynne Godley, Fred Harrison, Michael Hudson, Eric Janszen, Med Jones, Steve Keen, Jakob Broechner Madsen & Jens Kjaer Sørensen, Kurt Richebächer, Nouriel Roubini, Peter Schiff, and Robert Shiller.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Shiller, a founder of the Case–Shiller index that measures home prices, wrote an article a year before the collapse of Lehman Brothers in which he predicted that a slowing U.S. housing market would cause the housing bubble to burst, leading to financial collapse.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Peter Schiff regularly appeared on television in the years before the crisis and warned of the impending real estate collapse.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The Austrian School regarded the crisis as a vindication and classic example of a predictable credit-fueled bubble caused by laxity in monetary supply.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] There were other economists that did warn of a pending crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The former Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, Raghuram Rajan, had predicted the crisis in 2005 when he became chief economist at the International Monetary Fund.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 2005, at a celebration honoring Alan Greenspan, who was about to retire as chairman of the US Federal Reserve, Rajan delivered a controversial paper that was critical of the financial sector.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In that paper, Rajan "argued that disaster might loom".
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Rajan argued that financial sector managers were encouraged to "take risks that generate severe adverse consequences with small probability but, in return, offer generous compensation the rest of the time.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] He also took action against the establishment view by making a big financial bet on banking stocks and making a fortune from the crisis ("They didn't listen, so I took their money").
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Popular articles published in the mass media have led the general public to believe that the majority of economists have failed in their obligation to predict the financial crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] For example, an article in *The New York Times* noted that economist Nouriel Roubini warned of such crisis as early as September 2006, and stated that the profession of economics is bad at predicting recessions.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] According to *The Guardian*, Roubini was ridiculed for predicting a collapse of the housing market and worldwide recession, while *The New York Times* labelled him "Dr.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In a 2012 article in the journal *Japan and the World Economy*, Andrew K.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Spiegel used a Multiple Indicator Multiple Cause (MIMIC) model on a cross-section of 107 countries to evaluate potential causes of the 2008 crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The authors examined various economic indicators, ignoring contagion effects across countries.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Despite the fact that we use a wide number of possible causes in a flexible statistical framework, we are unable to link most of the commonly cited causes of the crisis to its incidence across countries.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The first visible institution to run into trouble in the United States was the Southern California–based IndyMac, a spin-off of Countrywide Financial.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Before its failure, IndyMac Bank was the largest savings and loan association in the Los Angeles market and the seventh-largest mortgage loan originator in the United States.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The failure of IndyMac Bank on July 11, 2008, was (until the crisis precipitated even larger failures) the fourth-largest bank failure in United States history, and the second-largest failure of a regulated thrift.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank's parent corporation was IndyMac Bancorp until the FDIC seized IndyMac Bank.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy in July 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bank was founded as Countrywide Mortgage Investment in 1985 by David S.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Loeb and Angelo Mozilo as a means of collateralizing Countrywide Financial loans too big to be sold to Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] In 1997, Countrywide spun off IndyMac as an independent company run by Mike Perry, who remained its CEO until the downfall of the bank in July 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The primary causes of its failure were largely associated with its business strategy of originating and securitizing Alt-A loans on a large scale.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This strategy resulted in rapid growth and a high concentration of risky assets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] From its inception as a savings association in 2000, IndyMac grew to the seventh largest savings and loan and ninth largest originator of mortgage loans in the United States.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] During 2006, IndyMac originated over $90 billion (~$134 billion in 2024) of mortgages.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac often made loans without verification of the borrower's income or assets, and to borrowers with poor credit histories.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Appraisals obtained by IndyMac on underlying collateral were often questionable as well.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] As an Alt-A lender, IndyMac's business model was to offer loan products to fit the borrower's needs, using an extensive array of risky option-adjustable-rate mortgages (option ARMs), subprime loans, 80/20 loans, and other nontraditional products.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Ultimately, loans were made to many borrowers who simply could not afford to make their payments.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The thrift remained profitable only as long as it was able to sell those loans in the secondary mortgage market.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac resisted efforts to regulate its involvement in those loans or tighten their issuing criteria: see the comment by Ruthann Melbourne, Chief Risk Officer, to the regulating agencies.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On May 12, 2008, in the "Capital" section of its last 10-Q, IndyMac revealed that it may not be well capitalized in the future.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that during April 2008, Moody's and Standard & Poor's downgraded the ratings on a significant number of Mortgage-backed security (MBS) bonds—including $160 million (~$228 million in 2024) issued by IndyMac that the bank retained in its MBS portfolio.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac concluded that these downgrades would have harmed its risk-based capital ratio as of June 30, 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Had these lowered ratings been in effect on March 31, 2008, IndyMac concluded that the bank's capital ratio would have been 9.27% total risk-based.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac warned that if its regulators found its capital position to have fallen below "well capitalized" (minimum 10% risk-based capital ratio) to "adequately capitalized" (8–10% risk-based capital ratio) the bank might no longer be able to use brokered deposits as a source of funds.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Senator Charles Schumer (D-NY) later pointed out that brokered deposits made up more than 37% of IndyMac's total deposits, and asked the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) whether it had considered ordering IndyMac to reduce its reliance on these deposits.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $18.9 billion in total deposits reported on March 31, Senator Schumer would have been referring to a little over $7 billion in brokered deposits.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the breakout of maturities of these deposits is not known exactly, a simple averaging would have put the threat of brokered deposits loss to IndyMac at $500 million a month, had the regulator disallowed IndyMac from acquiring new brokered deposits on June 30.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac was taking new measures to preserve capital, such as deferring interest payments on some preferred securities.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Dividends on common shares had already been suspended for the first quarter of 2008, after being cut in half the previous quarter.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The company still had not secured a significant capital infusion nor found a ready buyer.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac reported that the bank's risk-based capital was only $47 million above the minimum required for this 10% mark.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] But it did not reveal some of that $47 million (~$67 million in 2024) capital it claimed it had, as of March 31, 2008, was fabricated.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] When home prices declined in the latter half of 2007 and the secondary mortgage market collapsed, IndyMac was forced to hold $10.7 billion (~$15.5 billion in 2024) of loans it could not sell in the secondary market.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Its reduced liquidity was further exacerbated in late June 2008 when account holders withdrew $1.55 billion (~$2.21 billion in 2024) or about 7.5% of IndyMac's deposits.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] This bank run on the thrift followed the public release of a letter from Senator Charles Schumer to the FDIC and OTS.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The letter outlined the Senator's concerns with IndyMac.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] While the run was a contributing factor in the timing of IndyMac's demise, the underlying cause of the failure was the unsafe and unsound way it was operated.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac announced the closure of both its retail lending and wholesale divisions, halted new loan submissions, and cut 3,800 jobs.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On July 11, 2008, citing liquidity concerns, the FDIC put IndyMac Bank into conservatorship.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] A bridge bank, IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB, was established to assume control of IndyMac Bank's assets, its secured liabilities, and its insured deposit accounts.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC announced plans to open IndyMac Federal Bank, FSB on July 14, 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Until then, depositors would have access to their insured deposits through ATMs, their existing checks, and their existing debit cards.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Telephone and Internet account access was restored when the bank reopened.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The FDIC guarantees the funds of all insured accounts up to US$100,000, and declared a special advance dividend to the roughly 10,000 depositors with funds in excess of the insured amount, guaranteeing 50% of any amounts in excess of $100,000.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Yet, even with the pending sale of Indymac to IMB Management Holdings, an estimated 10,000 uninsured depositors of Indymac are still at a loss of over $270 million.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] With $32 billion in assets, IndyMac Bank was one of the largest bank failures in American history.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] IndyMac Bancorp filed for Chapter 7 bankruptcy on July 31, 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Initially the companies affected were those directly involved in home construction and mortgage lending such as Northern Rock and Countrywide Financial, as they could no longer obtain financing through the credit markets.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Over 100 mortgage lenders went bankrupt during 2007 and 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Concerns that investment bank Bear Stearns would collapse in March 2008 resulted in its fire-sale to JP Morgan Chase.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] The financial institution crisis hit its peak in September and October 2008.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Several major institutions either failed, were acquired under duress, or were subject to government takeover.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] These included Lehman Brothers, Merrill Lynch, Fannie Mae, Freddie Mac, Washington Mutual, Wachovia, Citigroup, and AIG.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] On October 6, 2008, three weeks after Lehman Brothers filed the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history, Lehman's former CEO Richard S.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld Jr. found himself before Representative Henry A.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Waxman, the California Democrat who chaired the House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform.
[src:portsmouth/2008-financial-crisis-p03] Fuld said he was a victim of the collapse, blaming a "crisis of confidence" in the markets for dooming his firm.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A census of the population of the United Kingdom is taken every ten years.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The **2011 census** was held in all countries of the UK on 27 March 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It was the first UK census which could be completed online via the Internet.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics (ONS) is responsible for the census in England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) is responsible for the census in Scotland, and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA) is responsible for the census in Northern Ireland.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is the executive office of the UK Statistics Authority, a non-ministerial department formed in 2008 and which reports directly to Parliament.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS is the UK Government's single largest statistical producer of independent statistics on the UK's economy and society, used to assist the planning and allocation of resources, policy-making and decision-making.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] ONS designs, manages and runs the census in England and Wales.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In its capacity as the national statistics office for the United Kingdom, ONS also compiles and releases census tables for the United Kingdom when the data from England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are complete.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In the run-up to the census both the main UK political parties expressed concerns about the increasing cost and the value for money of the census, and it was suggested that the 2011 census might be the last decennial census to be taken.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results from the 2011 census, age and sex, and occupied households estimates for England and Wales and Northern Ireland, were released on 16 July 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first results for Scotland, and the first UK-wide results, were published on 17 December 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed and specialised data were published from 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Registrar General John Rickman conducted the first census of Great Britain's population, and was responsible for the ten-yearly reports published between 1801 and 1831.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the first 100 years of census-taking the population of England and Wales grew more than threefold, to around 32 million, and that of Scotland, where a separate census has been carried out since 1861, to about 4.5 million.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 1911 onwards rapid social change, scientific breakthroughs, and major world events affected the structure of the population.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A fire that destroyed census records in 1931, and the declaration of war in 1939, made the 1951 census hugely significant in recording 30 years of change over one of the most turbulent periods in British history.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 1971 census was run by the newly created Office of Population Censuses and Surveys (OPCS), a body formed by the merger of the General Register Office and Government Social Survey.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 1996 the Office for National Statistics (ONS) was formed by merging the Central Statistical Office (CSO), OPCS and the statistics division of the Department of Employment; the first census it ran was in 2001.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2008 the UK Statistics Authority was established as an independent body.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A population census is a key instrument for assessing the needs of local communities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] When related to other data sources such as housing or agricultural censuses, or sample surveys, the data becomes even more useful.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Most countries of the world take censuses: the United Nations recommends that countries take a census at least once every ten years.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Twenty-one out of 40 countries in Europe are engaged in the 2010–2011 census round The design for the 2011 census reflected changes in society since 2001 and asked questions to help paint a detailed demographic picture of England and Wales, as it stood on census day, 27 March 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Data collected by the census is used to provide statistical outputs which central government uses to plan and allocate local authority services funding, and which local authorities themselves use to identify and meet the needs of their local communities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Other organisations that use census data include healthcare organisations, community groups, researchers and businesses.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questionnaires, including people's personal information, are kept confidential for 100 years before being released to the public, providing an important source of information for historical, demographic and genealogy research.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for England and Wales included around 25 million households.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] People could complete and submit their questionnaire online, or fill it in on paper and post it back in a pre-addressed envelope.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Guidance was provided online and through the census helpline.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Completed questionnaires were electronically tracked and field staff followed up with households that did not return a questionnaire.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In these cases field staff delivered and collected questionnaires and, where needed, provided advice or assistance in completing the questionnaire.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] There was a legal requirement to complete the 2011 census questionnaire, under the terms of the Census Act 1920.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] As at 27 March 2011 everyone who had lived or intended to live in the country for three months or more was required to complete a questionnaire.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Failure to return a completed questionnaire could lead to a fine and criminal record.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Lockheed Martin UK, the UK arm of US-based aerospace, defence, security, and technology company Lockheed Martin was awarded the contract to provide services for the census comprising questionnaire printing, a customer contact centre and data capture and processing.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The contract was valued at £150 million, approximately one third of the total £482 million census budget.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Concerns were raised during contract negotiations that the US PATRIOT Act could be used to force Lockheed Martin to reveal census data to US authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several groups called for a boycott of the census over the involvement of Lockheed Martin, including the Stop the War Coalition, and the Christian thinktank Ekklesia.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The groups were concerned about sharing data with a company involved in surveillance and data processing for the CIA and FBI; and also providing funding to an arms company making nuclear missiles and cluster bombs.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Green Party also objected, and campaigned unsuccessfully to stop Lockheed Martin getting the contract, although no decision was made about whether or not to call for a boycott.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Census Alert campaign group also decided against calling for a boycott.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy said a boycott would be counter-productive, as the census is used to distribute funding to local services.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Liberal Conspiracy reports that a council may lose £22,000 over 10 years for each person who does not complete the census.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The census for England and Wales was trialled in 135,000 households in Lancaster, the London Borough of Newham and Anglesey on 11 October 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A test was also carried out in Birmingham at the same time.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The questions for the 2011 census were the same as those trialled in the 2009 Census Rehearsal.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Order for the 2011 Census (including the proposed question topics, census date and who should complete the questionnaire) was laid before Parliament in October 2009 and was approved by Parliament and became law in December 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Capita Group was contracted by ONS to recruit, train and administer the pay for the 35,000 temporary ONS workers who worked as field staff for the 2011 census.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The total cost of the 2011 census in England and Wales over the period from 2004/05 to 2015/16 is estimated to be £482 million.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This is more than twice the £210m spent on the 2001 census.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This breaks down to a cost of 87 pence per person, per year (over the life of the census – ten years).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] "The cost equates to about 87p a year per person, demonstrating excellent value for money.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The per capita costs in the UK are less than for many other European countries that carry out similar censuses.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In summary, this census will meet crucial requirements for statistical information that Government and others cannot do without." Minister of State, Cabinet Office (Angela E.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Both the main UK political parties had expressed concerns about the rising costs and value of a ten-yearly census, and on coming into office the UK coalition government had gone as far as suggesting that the 2011 census might be the last of its kind.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In July 2010 the UK government asked ONS to explore other methods of measuring the population.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 the three national statistics bodies, ONS, GROS and NISRA set up a co-ordinated research project known as Beyond 2011.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The project reported its findings in March 2014 and recommended that a UK-wide census in 2021 should take place, and that better use should be made of other demographic data sources.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The general style of the questionnaire was similar to that of the 2001 census.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A rehearsal questionnaire was released in 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Several new identity and status options were included for the first time.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2001 only 38 people were reported to have been prosecuted for refusing to complete a questionnaire.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In 2011 those who refused to complete the census questionnaire or included false information could face a fine of up to £1,000.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A team of compliance staff were recruited to follow up by visiting those householders who refused to complete a questionnaire or where their questionnaire was not returned or completed correctly.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Advertising promoted the notion of how the UK 2011 census would help to shape Britain's future in areas such as healthcare and education.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] TV adverts, for example, depicted Origami, in census colours, forming objects including school computers and buses.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A short sentence under the census logo informed the viewer that the census was a duty that must be undertaken.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] From 7 April 2011 advertising focused on reminding people to complete and return by post or submit online.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A question about the number of bedrooms a household has, as well as the names, gender and birth dates of any overnight guests was criticised as "bedroom snooping" by the Conservative Party in opposition.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Although some 37,000 people recorded their identity as Cornish by manually writing it on the form in the 2001 census, no tick-box was provided in 2011 to select Cornish as a White British national identity, despite campaigns.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] As a consequence, posters were created by the census organisation and Cornwall Council which advised residents of how they could identify themselves as Cornish by writing it in the ethnicity, national identity and main language sections.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, people could record Cornwall as their country of birth.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] During the consultation on the 2011 census the British Humanist Association raised several concerns about question 20, "What is your religion?".
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA argued it was a leading question, and suggested that it should be phrased as two questions, "Do you have a religion?" and "If so, what is it?".
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It contended that by placing the religion question near the ethnicity question it would encourage some responders to associate religion with cultural identity.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The BHA also ran adverts during March 2011 encouraging the use of the 'no religion' box in the questionnaire.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland had 59 questions in total.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] 14 were about the household and its accommodation and 45 questions were for each individual member of the household to complete.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The rehearsal was held on Sunday 11 October 2009 in two areas, Derriaghy and Moy & Benburb, covering approximately 5,000 households.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census for Northern Ireland costing around £21.8 million over the six-year period 2008–2014.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Over the ten-year cycle the cost is expected to be about £25 million.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In Scotland, a wholly owned subsidiary of information technology company CACI was contracted to gather information.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] CACI "provided interrogators who worked at Abu Ghraib prison at the height of the prisoner abuse scandal".
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 Scotland census asked 13 household questions and up to 35 questions for each individual.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Plans were rehearsed in west Edinburgh and Lewis and Harris.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The 2011 census was the first to include a question asking about the ability to read, write and understand the Scots language alongside the question for ability in Scottish Gaelic and English languages.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Responsibility for the release of data from the 2011 census is split between the Office for National Statistics (ONS) for England and Wales, the General Register Office for Scotland (GROS) for Scotland and the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency (NISRA).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The ONS announced in March the release plan for the results of the 2011 census which stated in July 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA made a similar announcement with identical release plan.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In June 2012 GROS advised on its release plan which commences in December 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The releases will comprise data sets enabling the standard comparison with previous census data reports as well as over a hundred new data sets based on the new questions asked in the 2011 census.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] NISRA, ONS and GROS each publish a schedule stating what documents they will release and when.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Those documents are called a "prospectus".
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each prospectus is not fixed, but changes as schedules are changed or documents are late.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The prospectuses are linked to in the table below.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The Office for National Statistics is responsible for publishing United Kingdom wide 2011 census data.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] These are co-ordinated releases coinciding with data published by the three national statistical authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population data including data for males and females for the United Kingdom and revised estimates England, Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population numbers (rounded), by five-year age bands, sex and densities and household sata at national and local authority level.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates (unrounded) by single year of age and sex for the UK and all local authorities (or equivalent) in the UK, along with UK historic population pyramids (1951–2011).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 1 – Census Profiles; Population, People and Places, Health and Social Care, Travel and Transport.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] National and Local Authority geographies.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 2 – Census Profiles; Qualifications and Labour Market.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and Quick statistics Part 3 – Multivariate, Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for: Living arrangements; Household composition; and Accommodation type.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A series of further releases, subsequent to the four main releases of 2011 Census statistics including migration tables, workplace tables, detailed religion and ethnic group tables, and statistics relating to alternative population bases.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Specialist products would include:- Small population groups; microdata; flow data (also known as origin-destination statistics).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It is also suggested that data organised around alternative population bases may be produced.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The original plans of the ONS, covering England and Wales, confirmed that there would be four stages of data release starting in July 2012 and running until October 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This was increased to five stages in October 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] A detailed commentary accompanies each release along with relevant reference materials.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally there will be graphic visualisations providing further clarification and comparison between different data sets and comparison over time using data from earlier censuses.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] There will also be more specialist reports and products.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Certain data bases will also be produced in the Welsh language.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick univariate (single parameter) statistics based on output levels, with release based on geography.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] (e.g. local authority, wards and parish/ community) tabulated by population count and percentages and accessible by post code.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key Statistics for local authorities in England and Wales comprising data which adds detail to the population estimates published in July 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It includes population information on international migration, age, ethnicity, national identity, health, housing and religion.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Wales, there is data on the Welsh language and population data on unitary authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for Output Areas (OAs) and for wards.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Background information covering families, general health and disability, unpaid care, language, occupation and industry, qualifications and economic activity.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics for postcode sectors, health areas and Welsh Government devolved constituencies, and the key statistics for national parks in England and Wales, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Statistical tables for non-UK short-term residents in England and Wales and quick statistics for England and Wales on national identity, passports held and country of birth, with a separate release for Wales only.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] More detailed cross tabulation of data topics: Migration; ethnicity, identity, language and religion; health; and Welsh tables.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed Characteristics tables for the themes of demography and families at local authority, MSOA and ward level.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] English language proficiency for regions, local authorities, 2011 Census Merged Wards and MSOAs in England and Wales.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The first Local Characteristics tables for the topics of ethnicity, identity, language and religion for Output Areas, unitary and local authorities and regions.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics tables for the topics of health and unpaid care for Output Areas.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Follow up to Release 3.2b on 12 July 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristic Tables for the topic of migration for Output Areas.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local Characteristics on travel to work and car and van availability for Output Areas.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the six main releases phases further supplementary, smaller scale and specialist releases including; Small population groups, Microdata (teaching files, safeguarded files and secure files), Origin-destination data, and Alternate population bases.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Northern Ireland were set out by the NISRA.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release phases are closely synchronised with those of the ONS for England and Wales with some marginal variations to allow for local administrative arrangements.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Usual resident population by single age and sex for Local Government Districts, etc.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Household number and size by geographic units.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key statistics for NI and Local Government Districts etc.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Quick statistics for all geographies and population and household estimates for lower geographies.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI-wide and all local authority and other geographies (including religion, identity and health).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Detailed characteristics for NI (including ethnicity, country of birth and language).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Remaining detailed characteristics for NI including labour market and housing.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] All outstanding detailed characteristics for the remaining geographic areas.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate local characteristic tables and detailed themes around: economic activity; country of birth; occupation; and unpaid care.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The release plans for Scotland were set out by the GROS Release phase dates are partly in sync with those of the other UK constituent country statistical authorities, however the first release was scheduled for six months after the first releases by the other authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Consequently, release of UK-wide data has been scheduled so as to coincide with release plans for Scotland's Census releases.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates, based on resident households, communal establishments and age bands.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Estimates of the usually resident population of Scotland rounded to the nearest thousand, broken down by age and sex.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] An estimate of the total population in each council area, rounded to nearest thousand.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population estimates by five-year age bands and sex for Scotland and each council area.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population and household changes since 2001 census.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Population dependency ratios for Scotland and each council area.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] First release of unrounded population estimates and household communal establishment numbers, by single year of age and sex.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] (First published as rounded data in December 2012 and March 2013).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics; Census Profiles; headcounts and geography products.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Comprising; Estimates by postcode and geography products.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] This release will represent the start of the dissemination of detailed census statistics for small areas.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for marriage and civil partnership, ethnicity, religion, language proficiency, country of birth and national identity, heath (excluding long-term health), age, arrival in UK, population and households, housing and accommodation, car and van ownership.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: Scotland, Council Areas and Health Boards.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Education and Labour Market.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All output areas and Data Zones.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Also the key and quick statistics for the remaining geographies of the topics covered in Release 2a.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Key and quick statistics tables for Living Arrangements and Travel to Work Methods.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Coverage: All levels of census geographies.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Multivariate statistics, comprising a combination of; age, sex, resident type, ethnic group, economic activity, general health and provision of unpaid care, country of birth, and occupation.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables for Qualifications, Employment and Economic Activity, Travel for Work and Study.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Local and Detailed Characteristics tables including; Travel to Work, Household, Qualifications and Long-term Health, Social Status and Economic Activity.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The United Kingdom Statistics Authority is responsible for coordinating the release of census data by the devolved statistics authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] It publishes UK-wide census data results via the Office for National Statistics (ONS) site.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The UK Data Service provides a central point of reference for all country-specific census data releases via its Learning Hub site.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Primary responsibility for country-specific 2011 census data rests with the statistical authorities for each of the UK's constituent countries.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Each authority has at least one dedicated central source from which data can be downloaded or ordered.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] For England and Wales the ONS provides the access to primary data via its 2011 census siteArchived 29 January 2016 at the UK Government Web Archive.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Additionally, data organised by local authority or post code is available on the Neighbourhood Statistics Archived 20 October 2010 at the Wayback Machine site, and nomis, a source of detailed census results which can be assembled into bespoke data sets.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] For Scotland the General Registrar Office for Scotland (GROS) part of National Records of Scotland (NRS) to maintain access via its Scotlands Census site, and for Northern Ireland the Statistics and Research Authority (NISRA) uses the Northern Ireland Neighbourhood Information Service (NINIS).
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The format of all the pre-defined statistical tables is standardised as far as practical across the publishing authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] Since the 2001 UK census the naming conventions for the tables have been revised following research into the approaches adopted by other census publishing bodies around the world.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] The statistical authorities are also making available bulk data in Comma-separated values (CSV) file format which can be downloaded from online data warehouse facilities.
[src:portsmouth/2011-united-kingdom-census] In addition to the standard releases and online bulk access the statistical authorities provide a commissioned data service whereby other data configurations can be purchased, under license, by customers and will subsequently be made freely available to other users.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A referendum on Scottish independence from the United Kingdom was held in Scotland on 18 September 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The referendum question was "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which voters answered with "Yes" or "No".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The turnout of 84.6% was the highest recorded for an election or referendum in the United Kingdom since the January 1910 general election, which was held before the introduction of universal suffrage.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 set out the arrangements for the referendum and was passed by the Scottish Parliament in November 2013, following an agreement between the devolved Scottish government and the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The independence proposal required a simple majority to pass.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] All European Union (EU) or Commonwealth citizens residing in Scotland age 16 or over could vote, with some exceptions, which produced a total electorate of almost 4,300,000 people.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was the first time that the electoral franchise was extended to include 16- and 17-year-olds in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Yes Scotland was the main campaign group for independence, while Better Together was the main campaign group in favour of maintaining the union.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Many other campaign groups, political parties, businesses, newspapers, and prominent individuals were also involved.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Prominent issues raised during the referendum included what currency an independent Scotland would use, public expenditure, EU membership, and North Sea oil.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An exit poll revealed that retention of the pound sterling was the deciding factor for those who voted No, while "disaffection with Westminster politics" was the deciding factor for those who voted Yes.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England were established as independent countries during the Middle Ages.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After fighting a series of wars during the 14th century, the two monarchies entered a personal union in 1603 (the Union of the Crowns) when James VI of Scotland also became James I of England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two nations were temporarily united under one government when Oliver Cromwell was declared Lord Protector of a Commonwealth in 1653, but this was dissolved when the monarchy was restored in 1660.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Scotland and England united to form the Kingdom of Great Britain in 1707 (Wales had already been unilaterally incorporated into England in the mid-16th century).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scots favoured union to solve the economic problems caused by the failure of the Darien scheme and the English favoured it to secure the Hanoverian line of succession.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Great Britain in turn united with the Kingdom of Ireland in 1801, forming the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Most of Ireland left the Union in 1922 to form the Irish Free State; consequently, the full name of the United Kingdom since 1927 is the *United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Labour Party was committed to home rule for Scotland in the 1920s, but it slipped down its agenda in the following years.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish National Party (SNP) was founded in 1934, but did not achieve significant electoral success until the 1960s.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A petition calling for home rule, the Scottish Covenant, was signed by 2,000,000 people (out of a population of 5,000,000) in the late 1940s.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As James Callaghan's Labour Government of the late 1970s was pressured by the SNP, Scottish devolution was, for the first time, seriously proposed.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In a 1979 referendum for a devolved Scottish Assembly, a narrow majority of votes were cast in favour of devolution, but this had no effect due to a requirement that the number voting 'Yes' had to exceed 40% of the total electorate.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] No further constitutional reform was proposed until Labour returned to power in a landslide electoral victory in May 1997.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A second Scottish devolution referendum was held later that year, as promised in the Labour election manifesto.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Clear majorities expressed support for both a devolved Scottish Parliament (74.3% in favour) and that Parliament having the power to vary the basic rate of UK income tax (63.5% in favour).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scotland Act 1998 established the new Scottish Parliament, first elected on 6 May 1999, with power to legislate on unreserved matters within Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A commitment to hold an independence referendum in 2010 was part of the SNP's election manifesto when it contested the 2007 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The press were largely hostile towards the SNP, with a headline for *The Scottish Sun* in May 2007 stating – beside an image of a hangman's noose – "Vote SNP today and you put Scotland's head in the noose".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As a result of that election, the SNP became the largest party in the Scottish Parliament and formed a minority government led by the First Minister, Alex Salmond.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP administration launched a 'National Conversation' as a consultation exercise in August 2007, part of which included a draft referendum bill, the *Referendum (Scotland) Bill*.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After this, a white paper for the proposed Referendum Bill was published, on 30 November 2009.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It detailed four possible scenarios, with the text of the Bill and Referendum to be revealed later.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The scenarios were: no change; devolution per the Calman Review; further devolution; and full independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government published a draft version of the bill on 25 February 2010 for public consultation; *Scotland's Future: Draft Referendum (Scotland) Bill Consultation Paper* contained a consultation document and a draft version of the bill.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The consultation paper set out the proposed ballot papers, the mechanics of the proposed referendum, and how the proposed referendum was to be regulated.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The third proposal was for full independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 3rd Scottish Parliament only 50 of 129 MSPs (47 SNP, 2 Greens, and Margo MacDonald) supported a referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government withdrew the bill in September 2010 after failing to secure opposition support.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP repeated its commitment to hold an independence referendum when it published its manifesto for the 2011 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Days before the election, Salmond said that legislation for a referendum would be proposed in the "second half of the parliament", as he wanted to secure more powers for the Scottish Parliament via the Scotland Bill first.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the election, the SNP won 69 of the 129 seats, securing a majority in a proportional representative voting system.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] UK Prime Minister David Cameron congratulated Salmond on his 'emphatic win', but pledged to campaign for the Union if the SNP carried out their pledge to hold a referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, the UK government offered to legislate to provide the Scottish Parliament with the powers to hold a referendum, providing it was 'fair, legal and decisive'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This would set 'terms of reference for the referendum', such as its question(s), elector eligibility, and which body would organise the vote.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As the UK government worked on legal details, including the timing of the vote, Salmond announced an intention to hold the referendum in the autumn of 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Negotiations continued between the two governments until October 2012, when the Edinburgh Agreement was reached.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum (Franchise) Act 2013 was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 27 June 2013 and received Royal Assent on 7 August 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 26 November 2013, the Scottish government published *Scotland's Future*, a 670-page white paper laying out the case for independence and the means by which Scotland might become an independent country.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Government announced on 21 March 2013 that the referendum would be held on Thursday 18 September 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Some media reports mentioned that 2014 would be the 700th anniversary of the Battle of Bannockburn and that Scotland would also host the 2014 Commonwealth Games and the 2014 Ryder Cup.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond agreed that the presence of these events made 2014 a "good year to hold a referendum".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Convicted prisoners were not able to vote in the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) had ruled that this restriction was unlawful, but Scottish judge Lord Glennie said that he believed the ECHR judgment would apply only to parliamentary elections.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Appeals against his ruling were rejected by the Court of Session in Edinburgh and the UK Supreme Court.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The normal voting age was reduced from 18 to 16 for the referendum, as it was a Scottish National Party policy to reduce the voting age for all elections in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The move was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Greens.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, Labour MSP Elaine Murray led a debate arguing that the franchise should be extended to Scots living outside Scotland, including the approximately 800,000 living in the other parts of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the House of Lords, Baroness Symons argued that the rest of the UK should be allowed to vote on Scottish independence because it would affect the whole country.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This argument was rejected by the UK government, as the Advocate General for Scotland Lord Wallace said that "whether or not Scotland should leave the United Kingdom is a matter for Scotland".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Wallace also pointed to the fact that only two of 11 referendums since 1973 had been across all of the United Kingdom.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Professor John Curtice cited the precedent of the 1973 Northern Ireland sovereignty referendum (the "border poll"), which allowed only those resident in a part of the UK to vote on its sovereignty.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was debate as to whether the Scottish Parliament had the power to legislate for a referendum relating to the issue of Scottish independence, as the constitution is a matter reserved to the UK Parliament.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government insisted in 2010 that they could legislate for a referendum, as it would be an "advisory referendum on extending the powers of the Scottish Parliament", whose result would "have no legal effect on the Union".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Lord Wallace, Advocate General for Scotland, said in January 2012 that holding a referendum concerning the constitution would be outside the legislative power of the Scottish Parliament and that private individuals could challenge a Scottish Parliament referendum bill.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two governments signed the Edinburgh Agreement, which allowed for the temporary transfer of legal authority.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Per the Edinburgh Agreement, the UK government drafted an Order in Council granting the Scottish Parliament the necessary powers to hold, on or before 31 December 2014, an independence referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The draft Order was approved by resolutions of both Houses of Parliament, and the Order ("The Scotland Act 1998 (Modification of Schedule 5) Order 2013"), was approved by Queen Elizabeth II at a meeting of the Privy Council on 12 February 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under the powers temporarily transferred from Westminster under the section 30 Order, the Scottish Parliament adopted the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Act was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 14 November 2013 and received Royal Assent on 17 December 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under section 36 of the Act, it came into force the day after Royal Assent.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission was responsible for overseeing the referendum, "with the exception of the conduct of the poll and announcement of the result, and the giving of grants.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In its role of regulating the campaign and campaign spending, the Electoral Commission will report to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] (...) The poll and count will be managed in the same way as [local] elections, by local returning officers (...) and directed by a Chief Counting Officer".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Edinburgh Agreement stated that the wording of the question would be decided by the Scottish Parliament and reviewed for intelligibility by the Electoral Commission.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government stated that its preferred question was "Do you agree that Scotland should be an independent country?" The Electoral Commission tested the proposed question along with three other possible versions.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Their research found that the "Do you agree" preface made it a leading question, which would be more likely to garner a positive response.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The question was amended to "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which the Electoral Commission found was the most neutral and concise of the versions tested.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 2010 Draft Bill, the Scottish government proposed that there would be one designated campaign organisation for each outcome, both of which would be permitted to spend up to £750,000 on their campaign and to send one free mailshot to every household or voter in the referendum franchise.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was to be no public funding for campaigns.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Registered political parties were each to be allowed to spend £100,000.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This proposed limit on party spending was increased to £250,000 in 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In 2013, new proposals by the Electoral Commission for the 16-week regulated period preceding the poll were accepted.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] They allowed the two designated campaign organisations to spend up to £1.5 million each and for the parties in Scotland to spend the following amounts: £1,344,000 (SNP); £834,000 (Labour); £396,000 (Conservatives); £201,000 (Liberal Democrats); £150,000 (Greens).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An unlimited number of other organisations could register with the Electoral Commission, but their spending was limited to £150,000.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Groups spending more than £250,000 were required to submit audited returns to the Commission by 18 March 2015.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] According to the Scottish government's consultation paper published on 25 February 2010, the cost of the referendum was "likely to be around £9.5 million", mostly spent on running the poll and the count.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Costs would also include the posting of one neutral information leaflet about the referendum to every Scottish household, and one free mailshot to every household or voter in the poll for the designated campaign organisations.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In April 2013, the projected cost of the referendum was £13.3 million; the final administrative cost was £15.85 million.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scottish independence, Yes Scotland, was launched on 25 May 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Its chief executive was Blair Jenkins, formerly the Director of Broadcasting at STV and Head of News and Current Affairs at both STV and BBC Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign was supported by the SNP, the Scottish Green Party (which also created "its own pro-independence campaign to run alongside Yes Scotland") and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] At its launch, Salmond stated that he hoped one million people in Scotland would sign a declaration of support for independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 22 August 2014, Yes Scotland announced that the one million target had been surpassed.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scotland remaining in the UK, Better Together, was launched on 25 June 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was led by Alistair Darling, former Chancellor of the Exchequer, and had support from the Conservative Party, Labour Party and Liberal Democrats.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Political advertising on television and radio in the UK was prohibited by the Communications Act 2003, with the exception of permitted party political broadcasts.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Three major cinema chains stopped showing adverts by referendum campaign groups after receiving negative feedback from their customers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In December 2013, the Better Together campaign declared that it had received donations of £2,800,000.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Six-figure contributions were made by businessmen Ian Taylor and Donald Houston, and by author C.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Almost 27,000 donations of under £7,500 had been received by the same date.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Rowling, who announced in June 2014 that she had given £1,000,000 to the Better Together campaign.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the following month, whisky distiller William Grant & Sons announced a donation of approximately £100,000.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 12 August 2014, Better Together announced that it had raised enough money to cover the maximum spending permitted and was no longer accepting donations.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was attributed in part to a large number of small donations being received after the first televised debate between First Minister Alex Salmond and Labour MP Alistair Darling.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of May 2014, the Yes Scotland campaign had declared £4,500,000 in cash donations.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] EuroMillions lottery-winners Chris and Colin Weir gave £3,500,000.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A six-figure donation was given by investment fund manager Angus Tulloch; approximately 18,000 donations of less than £7,500 had been made by the same date.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Voting for the referendum commenced on 27 August 2014, with the receipt of ballots by postal voters.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of 15 August, 680,235 eligible voters had registered for postal voting, a 20% increase compared with March 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] During the postal vote phase, Police Scotland arrested a man from Glasgow on suspicion of selling his vote on eBay.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The registration deadline for referendum voters was 2 September 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Several councils reported the processing of "unprecedented" numbers of new registrations, while others received "tens of thousands" of applications in the final week.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The UK Government said that, if a simple majority of the vote was in favour of independence, then 'Scotland would become an independent country after a process of negotiations'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] If the majority opposed independence, Scotland would remain part of the United Kingdom.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Further powers would be devolved to the Scottish Parliament as a result of the Scotland Act 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission prepared an information leaflet which confirmed that the UK and Scottish governments had reached agreement on these points.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Cameron said in May 2014 that he believed that the referendum would be 'irreversible and binding'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the week before the referendum, both sides said they would abide by the result.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond said that it was a 'once in a generation' event, citing the precedent of the two devolution referendums in 1979 and 1997.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the event of a majority for Yes, the Scottish Government had proposed an independence date of 24 March 2016.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was suggested that, after negotiations concluded, the UK Parliament would legislate for Scottish independence to take place on the date that had been negotiated.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A report by a UK House of Lords committee published in May 2014 said that the UK could opt to delay the independence date.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, as part of a European Union (EU) member state, Scottish farmers received £583 million in subsidy payments from the EU under the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Annual CAP payments are made to the UK, which then determines how much to allocate to each of the devolved administrations, including Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the last CAP agreement, farmers in the UK qualified for additional convergence payments because Scottish farmers received a lower average single farm payment per hectare, mainly due to the mountainous terrain in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence therefore believed that an independent Scotland would receive greater agricultural subsidies as an independent state.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Opponents of independence believed that Scottish farmers benefited from the Union because the UK was one of the larger EU member states, and therefore had a greater say in CAP negotiations.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] They also questioned whether an independent Scotland would immediately receive full subsidy payments from the EU, as recent new member states had their subsidies phased in.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the independence referendum, the UK had some opt-outs from EU policies.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] One was the opt-out from the Schengen Area, meaning there were full passport checks for travellers from other EU countries except the Republic of Ireland, which was part of a Common Travel Area (CTA) with the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that an independent Scotland would remain outside the Schengen Area and remain inside the CTA, ensuring that no passport controls would be needed at the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon commented that an independent Scotland would negotiate with the EU to have the same visa arrangements as the UK has.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Carmichael, the Secretary of State for Scotland, said in January 2014 that it would make sense for Scotland to be in the CTA, but it would have to operate similar immigration policies to the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This position was supported by Home Secretary Theresa May, who said in March 2014 that passport checks should be introduced if Scotland adopted a looser immigration policy.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Conservative MP Richard Bacon said there would be "no reason" for border controls to be implemented.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the white paper *Scotland's Future*, the Scottish government pledged to expand childcare provision in an independent Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The paper stated that this policy would cost £700 million, but that this would be financed by increased tax revenue from an additional 100,000 women returning to work.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In March 2014, the National Day Nurseries Association said that the plan could not be implemented unless greater funding was provided by local authorities to private nurseries.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Scottish Parliament Information Centre questioned the economic benefit of the policy, pointing out that there were only 64,000 mothers of children aged between 1 and 5 who were economically inactive.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that all British citizens who had been born in Scotland would automatically become Scottish citizens on the date of independence, regardless of whether or not they were then living in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] British citizens "habitually resident" in Scotland would also be considered Scottish citizens, even if they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Every person who would automatically be considered a Scottish citizen would be able to opt-out of Scottish citizenship provided they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] UK Home Secretary Theresa May said the future policies of an independent Scottish government would affect whether Scottish citizens would be allowed to retain British citizenship.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] An analysis paper published by the UK government in January 2014 stated that it was likely that Scots would be able to hold dual citizenship; however, the duality was considered for all other countries, not specifically to the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The possibility of holding dual UK–Scotland citizenships could be subject to the "proof of affinity".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A YouGov poll in early September showed 25 per cent of the electorate believed MI5 was working with the British government to block independence, with many voters so fearful that the marks made by the pencils provided in polling stations would be tampered with that they brought their own pens.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP said that there was a defence underspend of 'at least £7.4 billion' between 2002 and 2012 in Scotland and that independence would allow the Scottish government to correct this imbalance.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In its white paper, the Scottish government planned that an independent Scotland would have a total of 15,000 regular and 5,000 reserve personnel across land, air and maritime forces by 2026.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In July 2013, the SNP proposed that there would be a £2.5 billion annual military budget in an independent Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons Defence Select Committee said that the £2.5bn budget was too low.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Andrew Murrison, UK Minister for International Security Strategy agreed and said it was 'risible' for the SNP to suggest it could create an independent force by 'salami-slicing' from current British armed forces units.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons defence committee also stated that Scottish independence would have a negative effect on its industry, while the UK government said it would not be willing to build warships in a foreign country.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The chief executive of Thales, one of Britain's largest defence suppliers, said that if Scotland became independent that this might raise questions about continued investment from his firm.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Royal United Services Institute said in 2012 that an independent Scotland could set up a Scottish Defence Force, comparable in size and strength to those of other small European states like Denmark, Norway, and Ireland, at an annual cost of £1.8 billion.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Dorcha Lee, a former colonel in the Irish Army, said that Scotland could eschew forming an army based on inherited resources from the British Army and instead follow an Irish model of a limited self-defence force.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the referendum, the Trident nuclear missile system was based at Coulport weapons depot and naval base of Faslane in the Firth of Clyde area.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP objected to having nuclear weapons on Scottish territory, but British military leaders said that there was no alternative site for the missiles.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In April 2014, several British military leaders co-signed a letter stating that forcing Trident to leave Scottish waters would place the UK nuclear deterrent in jeopardy.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] *Nowhere to Go*, a report by Scottish CND, concluded that the removal of Trident from Scotland would force unilateral nuclear disarmament by the United Kingdom, as the weapons would have no viable alternative base.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Royal United Services Institute said that relocating Trident would be 'very difficult, but not impossible' and estimated it would take about 10 years and create an additional cost of around £3 billion.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] According to a seminar hosted by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, that the Royal Navy would have to consider a range of alternatives, including disarmament.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A 2013 Scotland Institute report suggested a future Scottish government could be convinced to lease the Faslane nuclear base to the rest of the UK, in order to maintain good diplomatic relations and expedite NATO entry negotiations.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] SNP policy had historically been that an independent Scotland should not seek to obtain membership in NATO, but this was dropped after a vote by party members in 2012.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] MSPs John Finnie and Jean Urquhart resigned from the SNP over this policy change.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party and Scottish Socialist Party continued their opposition to NATO membership.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP position that Trident nuclear weapons should be removed from Scotland but that it should hold NATO membership was criticised by Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Patrick Harvie, co-convenor of the Scottish Green Party.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Malcolm Chalmers of the Royal United Services Institute said that 'pragmatists' in the SNP accepted that NATO membership would likely involve a long-term basing deal, enabling the UK to keep Trident on the Clyde.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was disputed by Mariot Leslie, a former UK permanent representative to NATO, who said that NATO would not want to disrupt its arrangements by excluding Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A UK government paper on security said that Police Scotland would lose access to the UK intelligence apparatus, including MI5, SIS, and GCHQ, and that an independent Scottish state would need to build security infrastructure.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Theresa May commented that an independent Scotland would have access to less security capability, but would not necessarily face a reduced threat.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] May also indicated that the British government would block Scotland from joining the Five Eyes intelligence-sharing alliance until Scotland had built up its own spying and intelligence infrastructure and was able to offer the alliance a "unique contribution".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Allan Burnett, former head of intelligence with Strathclyde Police and Scotland's counter-terrorism coordinator until 2010, said that 'an independent Scotland would face less of a threat, intelligence institutions will be readily created, and allies will remain allies'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Baroness Ramsay, a Labour peer and former case officer with MI6, said that the Scottish government's stance on intelligence was 'extremely naïve' and that it was "not going to be as simple as they think".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon said that Scotland would create a security service like MI5 to work alongside police and tackle terrorism, cyber-attacks and serious organised crime, and that creating an external intelligence agency would remain an option.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government and pro-independence campaigners said there was a democratic deficit in Scotland because the UK was a unitary state without a codified constitution.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP also called the unelected House of Lords an 'affront to democracy'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The 'democratic deficit' label has sometimes been used to refer to the period between the 1979 and 1997 UK general elections, during which the Labour Party held a majority of Scottish seats but the Conservative Party governed the whole of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in September 2013 that instances such as this amounted to a lack of democracy, and that 'people who live and work in Scotland are the people most likely to make the right choices for Scotland'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Menzies Campbell wrote in April 2014 that any democratic deficit had been addressed by creating the devolved Scottish Parliament, and that 'Scotland and the Scottish have enjoyed influence beyond our size or reasonable expectation' within the British government and the wider political system.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Conservative MP Daniel Kawczynski said in 2009 that the UK's asymmetric devolution had created a democratic deficit for England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was commonly known as the West Lothian question, which cited the anomaly whereby English MPs could not vote on affairs devolved to Scotland but Scottish MPs could vote on the equivalent subjects in England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Kawczynski also pointed out that the average number of voters in a parliamentary constituency was larger in England than in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the campaign, each of the three main UK parties conducted reviews of the UK constitution, with each recommending that more powers should devolve to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On the morning before a televised debate between Alex Salmond and Alistair Darling, Better Together published a joint statement.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Co-signed by the three main UK party leaders (David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg), it committed to granting Scotland increased power over domestic taxes and parts of the social security system.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Boris Johnson, the Conservative mayor of London, said he opposed giving the Scottish Parliament greater fiscal powers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the second televised debate, Salmond challenged Darling to specify which additional powers that could help create greater employment in Scotland would be granted if there was a 'no' vote.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During a visit to Scotland later that week, David Cameron promised more powers 'soon'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 8 September, former Prime Minister Gordon Brown suggested a timetable for the additional powers to be implemented in the event of a 'no' vote.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He proposed that work on a new Scotland Act would begin immediately after the referendum, resulting in the publication of a white paper by the end of November 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Two days before the referendum, the three main UK party leaders publicly pledged to introduce 'extensive new powers' by the timetable suggested and that the Barnett formula of public funding would continue.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A principal issue in the referendum was the economy.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Weir Group, one of the largest private companies based in Scotland, commissioned a study by Oxford Economics into the potential economic effects of Scottish independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It found that Weir would pay more corporation tax, despite the Scottish government's proposal to cut the rate of corporation tax, due to it no longer being able to offset losses in Scotland against profits in the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It also stated that independence would result in additional costs and complexity in the operation of business pension schemes.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report found that 70% of all Scottish exports are sold to the rest of the UK, which it said would particularly affect the financial services sector.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Standard Life, one of the Scottish financial sector's largest businesses, said in February 2014 that it had started registering companies in England in case it had to relocate some of its operations there.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In February 2014, the *Financial Times* noted that Scotland's per capita GDP was bigger than that of France when a geographic share of oil and gas was taken into account, and still bigger than that of Italy when it was not.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] As of April 2014, Scotland had a similar rate of unemployment to the UK average (6.6%) and a lower fiscal deficit (including as a percentage of GDP).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scotland performed better than the UK average in securing new Foreign Direct Investment in 2012–13 (measured by the number of projects), although not as well as Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] GDP growth during 2013 was lower in Scotland than in the rest of the UK, although this was partly due to an industrial dispute at the Grangemouth Refinery.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Deutsche Bank issued a report in the week before the referendum in which David Folkerts-Landau, the bank's chief economist, concluded: 'While it may sound simple and costless for a nation to exit a 300-year-old union, nothing could be further from the truth'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Folkerts-Landau said the economic prospects after a 'yes' vote were 'incomprehensible', and cited Winston Churchill's 1925 Gold Standard decision and the actions of America's Federal Reserve that triggered the Great Depression of the 1930s as mistakes of a similar magnitude.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Swiss financial services company UBS supported Deutsche Bank's position.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence said that Scotland had not realised its full economic potential because it was subject to the same economic policy as the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation published a report stating that UK economic policy had become 'overwhelmingly geared to helping London, meaning Scotland and other UK regions suffer from being denied the specific, local policies they need'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Later in January 2014, Colin Fox said that Scotland is 'penalised by an economic model biased towards the South East of England'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In November 2013, Chic Brodie said that Scotland was deprived of economic benefit in the 1980s after the Ministry of Defence blocked oil exploration off the West of Scotland, ostensibly to avoid interference with the UK's nuclear weapons arsenal.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Treasury issued a report on 20 May 2013 which said that Scotland's banking systems would be too big to ensure depositor compensation in the event of a bank failure.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report indicated that Scottish banks would have assets worth 1,254% of GDP, which was more than Cyprus and Iceland before the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It suggested Scottish taxpayers would each have £65,000 of potential liabilities during a hypothetical bailout in Scotland, versus £30,000 as part of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Economists including Andrew Hughes Hallett, Professor of Economics at St Andrews University, rejected the idea that Scotland would have to underwrite these liabilities alone.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He observed that banks operating in more than one country can be given a joint bailout by multiple governments.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In this way, France, Belgium, and the Netherlands collectively bailed out Fortis Bank and the Dexia Bank.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The American Federal Reserve System lent more than $1 trillion to British banks, including $446 billion to the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), because they had operations in the United States.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Robert Peston reported in March 2014 that RBS and Lloyds Banking Group might be forced to relocate their head offices from Edinburgh to London in case of Scottish independence, due to a European law brought in after the 1991 collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Financial groups including RBS, Lloyds, Clydesdale Bank, TSB, and Tesco Bank later announced that they planned to move their registered headquarters from Scotland to England if Scotland voted for independence, although most indicated that they had no immediate intention to transfer any jobs.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Another major economic issue was the currency that an independent Scotland would use.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The principal options were to establish an independent Scottish currency, join the euro, or retain the pound sterling (a form of currency substitution).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Throughout the 1990s and early 2000s, the SNP's policy was that an independent Scotland should adopt the euro, though this was relegated to a long-term rather than short-term goal by the party's 2009 conference.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] There was disagreement over whether Scotland would be required to join the euro if it became an EU member state in its own right.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] All new members are required to commit to joining the single currency, but they must first be party to ERM II for two years.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government argued that this was a *de facto* opt-out from the euro, because EU member states are not obliged to join ERM II.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] For example, the people of Sweden rejected adopting the euro in a 2003 referendum and its government subsequently refused to enter ERM II.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP favoured continued use of sterling in an independent Scotland through a formal currency union with the UK, with the Bank of England setting its interest rates and monetary policy and acting as its central bank.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In June 2012, Alistair Darling said voters in the rest of the UK could choose not to be in a currency union with Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Sir John Major rejected the idea of a currency union, saying it would require the UK to underwrite Scottish debt.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Gordon Brown said the SNP proposal would create a 'colonial relationship' between Scotland and Westminster.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones said in November 2013 that he would seek a veto on a currency union between Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Yes Scotland said that a currency union would benefit both Scotland and the rest of the UK, as Scotland's exports would boost the balance of payments, and consequently strengthen the exchange rate of sterling.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Meanwhile, UK economists and financial experts said the effect on the balance of payments and the exchange rate would be 'largely neutral'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Sterling fell by almost one cent against the US dollar in a day early in September 2014, due to an opinion poll showing a swing towards the Yes campaign.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The *Financial Times* reported a few days later that 'Asset managers, investors and pension savers are moving billions of pounds out of Scotland' because of fears that Scotland would leave the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The newspaper also reported that '"exit clauses" are being inserted into commercial property contracts in Scotland to allow buyers to scrap deals or renegotiate prices if voters opt for independence'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scottish Labour leader Johann Lamont said that any additional transaction costs would fall largely on Scottish companies, costing businesses in Scotland 11 times more than those in England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute of Directors said that any new transaction costs would 'pale in comparison to the financial danger of entering an unstable currency union'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Banking experts said that being the 'junior partner' in a currency arrangement could amount to 'a loss of fiscal autonomy for Scotland' if policy constraints were imposed on the Scottish state.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Angus Armstrong of the National Institute of Economic and Social Research wrote that the implicit constraints on its economic policy would be more restrictive than the explicit ones it faced as part of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in February 2014 that an independent Scotland in a currency union would retain tax and spending powers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Chancellor George Osborne, as well as equivalent post-holders in the two other main UK political parties, rejected the idea of a formal currency union with an independent Scotland in February 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls said the SNP's proposals for a currency union were 'economically incoherent' and that any currency option for an independent Scotland would be 'less advantageous than what we have across the UK today'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] After the three main UK political parties ruled out a formal currency union, the Adam Smith Institute said that the economies of Panama, Ecuador, and El Salvador 'demonstrate that the informal use of another country's currency can foster a healthy financial system and economy'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In September 2014, former European Commissioner Olli Rehn said that an independent Scotland would be unable to meet EU membership requirements if it shared sterling informally, as it would not have an independent central bank.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond disputed this, restating his belief that a sterling currency union would be formed and pledging to create the necessary financial institutions.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Socialist Party favoured an independent Scottish currency, pegged to sterling in the short term.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party said that keeping sterling as 'a short term transitional arrangement' should not be ruled out, but also that the Scottish Government should 'keep an open mind about moving towards an independent currency'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In early 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation described retention of the pound as a good transitional arrangement, but recommended the eventual establishment of an independent Scottish currency to 'insulate' Scotland from the UK's 'economic instability'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Other proponents of an independent Scottish currency included Yes Scotland chairman Dennis Canavan and former SNP deputy leader Jim Sillars.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 9 September 2014, Mark Carney, governor of the Bank of England, said that a currency union between an independent Scotland and the remainder of the UK would be 'incompatible with sovereignty'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He added that cross-border ties on tax, spending and banking rules are a prerequisite: 'You only have to look across the continent to look at what happens if you don't have those components in place ...
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At present under devolution, Scotland controls only 7% of our revenues.' Carney's comments received vocal support from Darling and the GMB trade union.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Barnett formula, introduced in the late 1970s, had resulted in higher per-capita public spending in Scotland than England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] If an allocation of North Sea oil revenue based on geography was included, Scotland also produced more per capita tax revenue than the UK average in the years immediately preceding the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute for Fiscal Studies reported in November 2012 that a geographic share of North Sea oil would more than cover the higher public spending, but warned that oil prices are volatile and that they are drawn from a finite resource.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Government Expenditure and Revenue Scotland report for 2012/13 found that North Sea oil revenue had fallen by 41.5% and that Scotland's public spending deficit had increased from £4.6 billion to £8.6 billion.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2012, the Scottish Government's Finance Secretary John Swinney prepared a confidential cabinet briefing paper on the financial impact of Scottish independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that an independent Scotland would face public spending cuts, lower pensions and welfare spending, and high levels of debt.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that Scotland's public finances would be heavily dependent on volatile and declining oil revenues, and suggested that the affordability of the state pension in an independent Scotland would be at risk.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report further warned that the SNP's plans for an oil fund under independence would "require some downward revision in current spending." Swinney's cabinet paper was kept secret before being leaked to the press in 2013, a year after it was drafted.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Darling, the leader of the Better Together campaign opposed to Scottish independence, described the leaked report as a "hammer blow" to the SNP's economic credibility.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A Scottish Government spokesman insisted that the report's findings had been "overtaken by events".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, the UK government published an analysis identifying a 'Union dividend' of £1,400 per year for each person in Scotland, mainly due to the higher level of public spending.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government disputed this analysis, saying that each Scot would be £1,000 better off per year under independence by 2030.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Three economic experts said that both estimates were possible, but they depended on unknown variables such as the division of UK government debt, future North Sea oil revenues, possible spending commitments of an independent Scotland and future productivity gains.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In its analysis, the UK government also estimated setup costs of £1.5 billion (1% of GDP) for establishing an independent state, or possibly £2.7 billion (180 public bodies costing £15 million each).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Patrick Dunleavy of the London School of Economics criticised the UK government's 'ludicrous' use of his research in arriving at the latter figure.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Treasury said that their main figure (£1.5 billion) was based on estimates by Robert Young of Western University.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two of the main unionist parties in Scotland called on the SNP to publish their own estimate of the setup costs of an independent state, but the Scottish government said that an estimate was not possible as the final bill would depend on negotiations with the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Dunleavy estimated immediate setup costs of £200 million in a report commissioned by *The Sunday Post*, with 'total transition costs' of between £600 million and £1,500 million in the first 10 years of independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit rating that an independent Scotland would merit also became a subject of debate.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit-rating agency Fitch said in 2012 that it could not give an opinion on what rating Scotland would have, because Scottish finances would largely depend on the result of negotiations between the UK and Scotland and specifically the division of UK assets and liabilities.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research published by Moody's in May 2014 said that an independent Scotland would be given an A rating, comparable with Poland, the Czech Republic and Mexico.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] An A rating would have been two grades below its then rating for the UK, which Moody's said would be unaffected by Scottish independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The UK government controlled most energy issues, although control over planning laws had allowed the Scottish government to prevent the construction of new nuclear power stations in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence wanted to retain a single energy market for the whole of Great Britain after independence, to maintain price stability and support for suppliers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that independence would threaten that single energy market.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister, professor of economics at Aberdeen University, said that although independence would affect the relationship, it was likely that there would be continued English demand for electricity generated in Scotland due to the lack of spare capacity elsewhere.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The second largest supplier of energy in the UK, SSE plc, believed that a single market would be the most likely outcome under independence, although it would require negotiations that may have led to changes to the existing system.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Caroline Flint said that independence would mean higher energy bills in Scotland, as its customers would have to pay more to support renewable energy in Scotland, which represented one-third of the UK total.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister said that bills were likely to increase across the whole of Great Britain because renewable schemes and new nuclear power stations in England were receiving higher subsidies than the power plants which were due for closure due to environmental regulations.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that there was a distinction between existing and proposed renewable schemes in that the existing schemes had already been paid for, whereas any new construction required the promise of subsidy from the consumer.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Energy and Climate Change Secretary Ed Davey said Scottish generators would no longer be eligible for UK subsidies, which would increase energy bills for consumers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Approximately 90% of the United Kingdom's North Sea oil fields were located in Scottish territorial waters.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The tax revenue generated from an offshore site was not counted within the nation or region nearest to it, but was instead allocated to the UK Continental Shelf.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The revenue from North Sea oil was used to support current expenditure, and the UK did not create a sovereign oil fund (as in Norway).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP believed that a portion of the revenues should have been invested in a sovereign oil fund.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government, citing industry body Oil and Gas UK, estimated in *Scotland's Future* that there were 24 billion barrels of oil equivalent still to be extracted.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Ian Wood, founder of oil services company Wood Group, said in August 2014 that he believed there were between 15 and 16.5 billion boe and that the impact from declining production would be felt by 2030.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2014, an investigation by industry recruitment website *Oil and Gas People* found that there were extensive oil reserves to the west of the Western Isles and Shetland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The report anticipated that the region would be developed within the next 10 years because of improvements in drilling technology, rig design and surveying.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP advocated that an independent Scotland should become a full member state of the European Union (EU) with some exemptions, such as not having to adopt the euro.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was debate over whether Scotland would be required to reapply for membership and whether it could retain the UK's opt-outs.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The European Commission (EC) offered to provide an opinion to an existing member state on the matter, but the UK government confirmed it would not seek this advice, as it did not want to negotiate the terms of independence in advance of the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was no precedent for an EU member state dividing into two sovereign countries after joining the EU.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence stated that an independent Scotland would become an EU member by treaty amendment under Article 48 of the EU treaties.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that this would not be possible and that an independent Scotland would need to apply for EU membership under Article 49, which would require ratification by each member state.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, Christina McKelvie, Convener of the European and External Relations Committee of the Scottish Parliament, asked Viviane Reding, Vice-President of the European Commission, whether Article 48 would apply.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Reding replied that EU treaties would no longer apply to a territory that secedes from a member state.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She also said that Article 49 would be the route to apply to become a member of the EU.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] José Manuel Barroso, president of the European Commission, said earlier that an independent Scotland would have to apply for EU membership, while the rest of the UK would continue to be a member.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2014, he reiterated that for Scotland to join the EU would be 'extremely difficult, if not impossible'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former prime minister Sir John Major suggested in November 2013 that Scotland would need to reapply for EU membership, but that this would mean overcoming opposition to separatism among other member states.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond cited a letter from Mario Tenreiro of the EC's secretariat general that said it would be legally possible to renegotiate the situation of the UK and Scotland within the EU by unanimous agreement of all member states.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Spain's European Affairs minister reiterated their position two days before the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir David Edward, a former European Court judge, said that the EU institutions and member states would be 'obliged' to start negotiations before independence took effect to decide the future relationship.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He said this would be achieved by agreed amendment of the existing Treaties (Article 48), rather than a new Accession Treaty (Article 49).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Graham Avery, the EC's honorary director-general, agreed with Edward.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Avery wrote a report, published by the European Policy Centre, which said that EU leaders would probably allow Scotland to be part of the EU because of the legal and practical difficulties that would arise from excluding it.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a research paper, Professor Sionaidh Douglas-Scott of Oxford University wrote that the EU law normally takes a 'pragmatic and purposive approach' to issues not already provided for by existing treaties.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, the Republic of Ireland's Minister of European Affairs, Lucinda Creighton, said that if Scotland were to become independent, it 'would have to apply for membership and that can be a lengthy process'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She later clarified those remarks, writing that she 'certainly did not at any stage suggest that Scotland could, should or would be thrown out of the EU'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that Barroso's comments on the legal position had 'no basis in the European treaties'.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, David Cameron committed the Conservative Party to a referendum before the end of 2017 on UK membership of the EU if they won the 2015 general election.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Legislation for an in/out EU referendum was approved by the House of Commons in November 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Studies showed some divergence in attitudes to the EU in Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, there was a majority for withdrawal in England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland said that the UK government plans for an EU referendum had caused "economic uncertainty" for Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During a CBI Scotland event attended by Cameron, businessman Michael Rake criticised him for creating uncertainty about EU membership.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In response to such criticism, Cameron pointed to examples of inward investment in the UK that he said was not happening in the rest of Europe.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some commentators suggested that the UK leaving the EU could undermine the case for Scottish independence, since free trade, freedom of movement and the absence of border controls between Scotland and England could no longer be assumed.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Responsibility for most aspects of health care was devolved to the Scottish Parliament when it was established in 1999.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government enacted health policies which were different from those in England, such as abolishing charges for prescriptions and elderly personal care.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] NHS Scotland was operationally independent of the NHS in the rest of the United Kingdom since the formation of the NHS in 1948.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence argued that independence was needed because possible reductions in the NHS budget in England would result in reduced funding for Scotland, which would make it difficult to maintain the existing service.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Harry Burns, a former chief medical officer for Scotland, said in July 2014 that he thought independence could be beneficial for public health because it may give people greater control of their lives.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, about 100 medical workers, including surgeons, consultant doctors, GPs, pharmacists, dentists, hospital porters and janitors joined a pro-independence campaign group called "NHS for Yes".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, opponents argued that a subsequent drop in funding to an independent Scottish Government would have a significantly larger effect upon the budget.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Concerns were also raised about the impact on the medical research sector in Scotland from the loss of UK wide research funding.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two days before the referendum, papers indicating "a funding gap of £400–£450m in the next two financial years, 2015–17", for Scotland's NHS, resulting from Scottish government policies, were leaked to the media.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A Scottish government spokesperson commented that the papers were from "part of the regular discussions among NHS leaders to plan for NHS Scotland's future".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents of independence said that being part of the UK was crucial in allowing Scots to obtain specialist treatment elsewhere in the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Although operationally independent, NHS Scotland had reciprocal arrangements in place with the NHS services in the rest of the UK and specialist services were shared.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders, a unionist campaign group, ran a cinema advert which claimed that Scots would find it more difficult to obtain treatment at the Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH), a London facility which provided specialist care for children.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders withdrew the advert after GOSH complained that it had not been consulted about the advert and stated that they had reciprocal health care agreements with numerous countries.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The white paper on independence proposed that an independent Scotland would open around 100 embassies around the world.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Prime Minister David Cameron suggested that an independent Scotland would be "marginalised" at the United Nations, where the UK is a permanent member of the Security Council.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Prime Minister John Major suggested that the UK could lose its permanent seat at the Security Council if Scotland became independent.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Forming a republic was favoured by some pro-independence political parties and organisations, including the Scottish Green Party and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP favoured an independent Scotland continuing to recognise Elizabeth II as Queen of Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Christine Grahame MSP said she believed that party policy was to hold a referendum on the matter, due to a 1997 SNP conference resolution.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some media reports suggested that the announcement on 8 September of the pregnancy of the Duchess of Cambridge with her second child would help pro-union sentiment.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Queen's official position on Scottish independence was neutral.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Just prior to the referendum, Elizabeth II said in a private conversation that she hoped people would "think very carefully about the future".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK State Pensions were managed by the UK government, paying £113.10 per week to a single person who is of state pension age in the 2013/14 tax year.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The state pension age for men was 65, but this was due to rise to 66 in 2020 and 67 by 2028.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research found that an independent Scotland could delay these increases, due to a lower life expectancy.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Scotland's Future* white paper pledged to maintain a state pension at a similar rate to the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former UK Prime Minister Gordon Brown said in April 2014 that Scotland had an above-average share of the public-sector pension bill and concluded that pensions would be protected by sharing risks and resources within the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK government pensions minister Steve Webb said in May 2014 that Scots would be entitled to the current levels of state pension after independence because they had accumulated rights within the existing system.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Webb went on to say that there would need to be negotiations between the UK and Scotland as to how these pensions would be paid.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In relation to private pension schemes, a report by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland expressed concern that there were no plans to deal with EU regulations that may affect the funding of cross-border defined benefit schemes.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The EC decided in March 2014 not to relax these regulations, which require cross-border schemes to be fully funded.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scotland hosted the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, less than two months before the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish team won a record number of gold medals, which the writer Alan Bisset said would help give voters more belief and confidence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *Sunday Herald* columnist Ian Bell took an opposing view, saying that sporting success would be unlikely to aid support for independence, due to the lengthy and passionate debate on the subject.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Labour first minister Henry McLeish published a report in May 2014 that found no obvious barriers to an independent Scotland competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] McLeish said that some athletes, particularly those in team sports, may choose to compete for the existing Great Britain team rather than Scotland, as they would be nationals of both states.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Gordon Brown pointed to the 2012 medal count for Great Britain, saying that it showed the success of the union.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish athletes were involved in 13 of the 65 medals won by Great Britain in 2012, but only three of those were won without assistance by athletes from other parts of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Chris Hoy said in May 2013 that it would "take time" for Scottish athletes to "establish themselves in a new training environment", and indicated that the good performance of Scottish athletes in the Great Britain team would not automatically translate into that of an independent Scotland team.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Hoy also said that he believed the lack of facilities and coaching infrastructure in Scotland would have to be addressed by an independent state.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The prospect of an independent Scotland raised questions about the future of the Northern Isles (Orkney and Shetland) and the Western Isles, island groups off the Scottish mainland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some islanders called for separate referendums to be held in the islands on 25 September 2014, one week after the Scottish referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, the Scottish Parliament published an online petition it had received calling for such referendums, which was supported by Shetland MSP Tavish Scott.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The proposed referendums would have asked islanders to choose from three options: that the island group should become an independent country; that it should remain in Scotland; or that (in the event of Scottish independence) it should remain in the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The third option would have implemented a conditional promise made in 2012 by an SNP spokesperson, who said that Orkney and Shetland could remain in the United Kingdom if their "drive for self-determination" was strong enough.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Politicians in the three island groups referred to the Scottish referendum as the most important event in their political history "since the inception of the island councils in 1975".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Angus Campbell, leader of the Western Isles, said that the ongoing constitutional debate offered the "opportunity for the three island councils to secure increased powers for our communities to take decisions which will benefit the economies and the lives of those who live in the islands".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a meeting of the island councils in March 2013, leaders of the three territories discussed their future in the event of Scottish independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] This included whether the islands could demand and achieve autonomous status within either Scotland or the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Among the scenarios proposed were achieving either Crown Dependency status or self-government modelled after the Faroe Islands, in association with either Scotland or the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle, Orkney's council leader, described pursuing Crown Dependency status as the least likely option, as it would threaten funding from the EU, which was essential for local farmers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alasdair Allan, MSP for the Western Isles, said independence could have a positive impact on the isles, as "crofters and farmers could expect a substantial uplift in agricultural and rural development funding via the Common Agricultural Policy if Scotland were an independent member state of the EU".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In July 2013, the Scottish government made the Lerwick Declaration, indicating an interest in devolving power to Scotland's islands.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By November, it had committed to devolving further powers to Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles in the event of independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle called for legislation to that effect to be introduced regardless of the referendum result.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He stated that he did not want such circumstances to arise, "and the best way to avoid this was to vote no in the referendum".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2012–13, Scottish universities received 13.1% of Research Councils UK funding.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alan Trench of University College London said that Scottish universities had received a "hugely disproportionate" level of funding and would no longer be able to access it following independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, suggested that independence would mean Scottish universities losing £210m in research funding.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Institute of Physics in Scotland warned that access to international facilities such as the CERN Large Hadron Collider, the European Space Agency, and European Southern Observatory could require renegotiation by the Scottish government.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It also expressed concerns about research funding from UK charities and the reaction of international companies with Scottish facilities.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government's education secretary, Michael Russell, said that Scotland's universities had a "global reputation" that would continue to attract investment after independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the principal of the University of Aberdeen said that Scottish universities could continue to access UK research funding through a "single research area" that crossed both nations' boundaries.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Bell, professor of economics at the University of Stirling, said that cross-border collaboration might continue, but Scottish universities could still lose their financial advantage.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Roger Cook of the Scotland Institute pointed out that although Scottish universities had received a higher share of Research Councils funding, they were much less dependent on this as a source of funding than their counterparts in England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professors from Scotland's five medical schools wrote an open letter warning that independence would mean Scotland's researcher base being "denied its present ability to win proportionately more grant funding".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Questions were asked whether Scotland, as an economy of a smaller size than the UK, would still support the same level of research activity, and what additional efforts might be required to establish a system of research councils "north of the border".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Jo Shaw, Salvesen chair of European institutions at the University of Edinburgh, noted that in smaller states, relationships between universities and research funders became "cosy", and led to a "corporatist" approach.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the time of the referendum, Students domiciled in Scotland did not pay tuition fees.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Students domiciled in the rest of the UK were charged fees of up to £9,000 per annum by Scottish universities, but those from other EU member states were not charged fees due to EU law.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] If Scotland had become an independent state, students from the rest of the UK would have been in the same position as students from the rest of the EU.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A University of Edinburgh study found that this would cause a loss in funding, which could have squeezed out Scottish students.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It concluded that the EU may allow a quota system for some specialist subjects, such as medicine, where there was a clear need for local students to be trained for particular careers, but that other subjects would not be eligible.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The study also found that their third suggestion would run against the spirit of the Bologna agreement, which aimed to encourage EU student mobility.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government stated in its white paper, *Scotland's Future*, that the present tuition fees arrangement would remain in place in an independent Scotland, as the EU allowed for different fee arrangements in "exceptional circumstances".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Ján Figeľ, a former EU commissioner for education, said in January 2014 that it would be illegal for an independent Scotland to apply a different treatment to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A report by a House of Commons select committee stated that it would cost an independent Scottish government £150 million to provide free tuition to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A group of academics campaigning for independence expressed concern that the present arrangements would not continue if Scotland stayed within the UK, due to public spending cuts in England and the consequential effects of the Barnett formula.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign argued that control of welfare policy would be a major benefit of independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies, independence would "give the opportunity for more radical reform, so that the [welfare] system better reflects the views of the Scottish people".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland and deputy first minister Nicola Sturgeon said the existing welfare system could only be guaranteed by voting for independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO), which represents charities, called for a separate welfare system to be established in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In November 2013, the Scottish government pledged to use the powers of independence to reverse key aspects of the Welfare Reform Act 2012, which was implemented across the UK despite opposition from a majority of Scotland's MPs.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It said it would abolish Universal Credit and the bedroom tax.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP also criticised Rachel Reeves, Labour's shadow secretary of state for work and pensions, for saying that a future UK Labour government would be even tougher on benefits than the Cameron–Clegg coalition government.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour politician Jim Murphy, a former Secretary of State for Scotland, said that he was "fiercely committed" to devolving welfare powers to the Scottish Parliament, but also warned that independence would be disruptive and would not be beneficial.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish Labour's Devolution Commission recommended in March 2014 that some aspects of the welfare state, including housing benefit and attendance allowance, should be devolved.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Feminist economist Ailsa McKay, a supporter of the Radical Independence movement, argued that an independent Scotland should change its welfare system dramatically by offering all its people a basic income.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A number of demonstrations in support of independence were co-ordinated following the announcement of the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally for Scottish Independence in September 2012 drew a crowd of between 5,000 and 10,000 people to Princes Street Gardens.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The event was repeated in September 2013; police estimated that over 8,000 people took part in the march, while organisers and the Scottish Police Federation claimed between 20,000 and 30,000 people took part in the combined march and rally.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally was criticised in both 2012 and 2013 for the involvement of groups like the Scottish Republican Socialist Movement and Vlaamse Volksbeweging.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Five days before the referendum vote, the Orange Order – a Protestant brotherhood – held a major anti-independence march and rally in Edinburgh.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It involved at least 15,000 Orangemen, loyalist bands and supporters from Scotland and across the UK, and was described as the biggest pro-Union demonstration of the campaign up to that date.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A rally for UK unity, organised by the Let's Stay Together campaign, was attended by 5,000 people in London's Trafalgar Square on the Monday preceding the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Similar events were held in London, Bristol, Leeds, Cardiff, Manchester and Belfast on the day before the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Jim Murphy conducted a Scotland-wide tour to campaign for the No side, intending to visit 100 towns and cities in 100 days before the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 28 August he suspended his tour, after being hit by an egg in Kirkcaldy, and it was resumed on 3 September.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Murphy said that he had been subjected to "co-ordinated abuse" from Yes supporters and pointed to evidence of this on social media.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together released footage of events in the tour where he was heckled by members of the public, some of whom called him a "traitor", "parasite", "terrorist" and "quisling".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Cameron said that "there's nothing wrong with a bit of heckling, but throwing things isn't necessarily part of the democratic process".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Salmond pointed out that people had "every entitlement to peaceful protest", but also said that "people shouldn't throw eggs at somebody full stop".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the launch of the Yes Scotland campaign in May 2012, Alex Salmond said that the case for independence would be driven by community activism and "online wizardry".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The not-for-profit and non-partisan *What Scotland Thinks* project tracked poll and survey data, including online activity, during the referendum campaign.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Using data from the Applied Quantitative Methods Network (AQMeN) research centre, the project compiled the social media activity of the two main campaigns, Yes Scotland and Better Together, by monitoring their respective Facebook and Twitter accounts since August 2013.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *What Scotland Thinks* published a report in February 2014 stating that the Yes Scotland campaign was gaining more Facebook likes.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Following the launch of the White Paper on 26 November, the average gap between the two Facebook pages grew from about 8,000 to about 23,000 by February 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Analysis of the campaigns' Twitter accounts showed the gap between the campaigns increased from approximately 8,000 followers in August 2013 to 13,804 followers in February 2014, in favour of Yes Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The project published a further report in June 2014 saying that greater online activity for Yes Scotland had continued.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor Michael Keating said in April 2014 that the pro-independence movement was visibly stronger and fighting a "ground war", while unionist supporters were fighting an "'air war' of facts and figures".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The launch of online celebrity videos from both viewpoints was reported by the media in mid-July 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The "Let's Stay Together" campaign group produced a YouTube video called "'Scotland, you're my best friend'", featuring John Barrowman, Ross Kemp and Eddie Izzard.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A pro-independence video was produced by Yes Scotland and appeared on the campaign's YouTube channel.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Titled "✘ on September 18th #voteYes", the video features 32 people, including David Hayman, Martin Compston and Stuart Braithwaite.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The pro-independence organisation National Collective was identified by the *Independent* newspaper as the initiators of an online hashtag campaign that began in mid-August 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing for the *Independent*, Antonia Molloy said that the previous "#IndyReasons" hashtag campaign served as the inspiration for the "#YesBecause" campaign that was observed on the Twitter, Facebook and Vine social media platforms.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] From 21 August, users were invited to explain their reasons for voting "Yes" and #YesBecause was trending on Twitter after an hour from the launch.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) reported on 22 August that a "#NoBecause" campaign emerged in opposition to the Collective.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Debates over the issue of independence took place on television, in communities, and within universities and societies since the announcement of the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The STV current affairs programme *Scotland Tonight* televised a series of debates: Nicola Sturgeon v Michael Moore, Sturgeon v Anas Sarwar, Sturgeon v Alistair Carmichael and Sturgeon v Johann Lamont.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 21 January 2014, BBC Two Scotland broadcast the first in a series of round-table debates, which was filmed in Greenock and chaired by James Cook.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign repeatedly called for a televised debate between UK Prime Minister David Cameron and First Minister of Scotland Alex Salmond.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] These calls for a one-on-one debate were dismissed by Cameron on the basis that the referendum is "for Scots to decide" and the debate should be "between people in Scotland who want to stay, and people in Scotland who want to go".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Calls for such a debate were also supported by former Prime Minister Gordon Brown who said it would be a "good idea".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together chairman Alistair Darling accused Salmond of "running scared" from debating him instead, although Sturgeon stated in 2013 that a Salmond–Darling debate would take place at some point.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Darling refused a public debate with Yes Scotland chairman Blair Jenkins.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UKIP leader Nigel Farage also challenged Salmond to debate, but Farage was dismissed by an SNP spokeswoman as "an irrelevance in Scotland".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After weeks of negotiation, a debate between Salmond and Darling was arranged.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The programme, titled as *Salmond & Darling: The Debate*, was broadcast by STV on 5 August 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The debate, moderated by Bernard Ponsonby, saw both politicians make opening statements and cross-examine each other before taking questions from the audience.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the end of the clash, they were both given the chance to make a closing speech.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Both campaign groups claimed victory in the debate.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A snap poll conducted by ICM stated Darling won the debate by 56% to 44%.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In his analysis of the ICM poll, Professor John Curtice detected little movement either way as a result of the debate.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A second debate between Salmond and Darling, titled *Scotland Decides: Salmond versus Darling* was shown on BBC One Scotland (and BBC Two in the rest of the UK) on 25 August, and was hosted by Glenn Campbell.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond was perceived to have won the debate, and a snap poll conducted by ICM Research stated Salmond won the debate by 71% to 29%.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, BBC Scotland chiefs appeared before a Scottish Parliament committee to face questions from MSPs about the broadcaster's coverage.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During that session, BBC Scotland director Ken MacQuarrie disputed the findings of Robertson's study, saying that its conclusions were largely based upon "flawed analysis" and had contained factual errors.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During the latter stages of the campaign there were further allegations by some independence supporters that the BBC – the UK's national broadcaster – was biased against Scottish independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In an interview for the *Sunday Herald*, Alex Salmond said he believed the BBC had been unconsciously biased against independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former BBC journalist Paul Mason commented: "Not since Iraq have I seen BBC News working at propaganda strength like this".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The BBC replied that "Our coverage of the referendum story is fair and impartial in line with the editorial guidelines".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Massie wrote in *The Spectator* that the BBC's coverage was consistent with their attitude towards other government proposals of such magnitude and that it was incumbent upon the Yes campaign to prove its assertions.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 29 June, several hundred independence supporters gathered in a demonstration outside BBC Pacific Quay, the main BBC studio in Glasgow, in protest at its alleged bias.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A week before the vote, BBC political editor Nick Robinson said in a news item that Salmond "didn't answer" his questions at a press conference.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Several thousand independence supporters then protested at the BBC Scotland headquarters, accusing the BBC of broadcasting pro-Union "propaganda" and "lies".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *The Independent* reported that the protesters accused Robinson of working "with the Treasury to spread lies about the dangers to business and financial services of an independent Scotland".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alastair Campbell said that the "organised protests" amounted to media censorship "not far off" Vladimir Putin's Russia, telling Twitter users they should "Vote YES for intimidation".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The National Union of Journalists (NUJ) asked people to think about the implications of alleging journalistic bias when its members were only asking difficult questions.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Robinson later expressed his "regret" at using the phrase "didn't answer" in his report and criticised the protests.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Speaking after the referendum, Yes Scotland chief executive Blair Jenkins said that he did not believe there was a "systemic bias" against Yes or any "corporate intent to disadvantage the Yes campaign".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In addition to the incidents described above, there were reports of intimidation during the campaign.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A survey of the 133 business leaders who signed a public letter backing the Union reported that half of respondents "said that they had felt intimidated or pressurised by SNP or the Yes campaign as a result of their views".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Daily Telegraph* reported that other businesspeople had been unwilling to express an opinion on the referendum publicly because they were concerned about a loss of business from the SNP-led Scottish government or local government.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The NUJ called for abuse and bullying of its members, which had been led by online attacks, to end, commenting that, "For the duration of the referendum there has been hostility to journalists doing their jobs".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Police Federation stated that criminal acts related to the referendum were few in number and criticised those "suggesting a minority of mindless idiots are representative of anything".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor John Curtice stated in January 2012 that polling showed support for independence at 32%–38% of the Scottish population, which represented a slight decline from 2007, when the SNP had first formed the Scottish government.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By 2012, there had been no poll evidence of majority support for independence, although the share "vehemently opposed to independence" had declined.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to Curtice, the polls were stable during most of 2013, with "no" leading by an average of 17% with a year to go.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Polling expert Nate Silver said in 2013 that the yes campaign had "virtually no chance" of winning the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After the referendum, Silver said that although his prediction had been proven "right" he had done little research beforehand.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The gap narrowed after the release of the Scottish government white paper on independence: an average of five polls in December 2013 and January 2014 gave 39% yes and 61% no, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The polls tightened further after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, George Osborne, stated in February that the UK government was opposed to a currency union; the average yes support increased to 43%, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was little movement in the following months, with the average continuing to show 43% yes and 57% no (excluding don't knows) in July 2014 and August 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In early September, polls indicated that the vote would be closer than had been indicated earlier.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 6 September a YouGov poll gave those in favour 47% versus 45% for those against; excluding those undecided, the figures were 51% and 49%, respectively.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The final polls, taken in the last few days of the campaign, indicated a lead for No of between 4% and 6%.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Soon after polling stations had closed, YouGov released a final poll that had been taken during the day of voting, indicating 46% Yes, 54% No.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing after the referendum, Nate Silver pointed out that the final margin of victory for No was greater than that indicated by the opinion polls.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He suggested that this could have been due to less enthusiastic voters being more pro-Union, which may not have been reflected in the polls.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Stephen Fisher, a sociology professor at Oxford University, noted in a study of other constitutional referendums that pollsters had tended to overestimate the "Yes" option.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2015, a poll carried out by YouGov found a slight majority of support for independence among people born in Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Independence Referendum Bill identified the convener of the Electoral Management Board for Scotland as chief counting officer for the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The chief counting officer, Mary Pitcaithly, was supported by a counting officer in each of the 32 local authority areas of Scotland, who was typically the chief executive for that local authority.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Voting took place between 07:00 and 22:00 BST in "polling places", which included schools, church halls, libraries and community centres.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Those who were still queuing when polls closed were not denied the chance to vote.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Votes from the 32 local government areas were counted and announced by each area separately.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Results came in during the early hours of 19 September, with the first result being from Clackmannanshire, and the last being from Highland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 55.3% voted against independence, with a turnout of 84.6%.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 28 of the 32 council areas voted "No", although the four areas that voted "Yes" (Dundee, Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and West Dunbartonshire) contained over 20% of the Scottish electorate.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The overall turnout of 84.6% was very high for Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Turnout was around 50–60% for elections to the Scottish and UK parliaments in the early 21st century.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The most recent United Kingdom general election with a comparable turnout was in 1950, when 83.9% voted.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The last ballot in the United Kingdom with a higher turnout than 84.6% was in January 1910, when no women and fewer men were allowed to vote (i.e., before universal suffrage applied to UK elections).
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Of the 32 areas, East Dunbartonshire had the highest turnout at 91.0%, and Glasgow the lowest at 75.0%.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An academic study, surveying 5,000 Scottish voters soon after the referendum, found that the majority for No was formed by an "unusual alliance" of the very young, average earners, Protestants and women.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The study supported polling evidence that there was a gender gap, but countered beliefs that higher earners had supported No and that younger voters had mostly voted Yes.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to John Curtice, polling evidence indicates that support for independence was highest among those aged in their late 20s and early 30s, with a higher No vote among those aged between 16 and 24.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was an age gap at the referendum, with elderly voters being the most likely to vote against independence and younger voters aged under 55, except for those aged between 16 and 24, generally being more in favour of independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This was picked up by other academics, with data from the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation study from 2012 indicating that the six most deprived local authorities in Scotland returned the highest Yes vote shares at the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This is an incomplete list as not all local authorities counted by ward or constituency.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The constituency results are primarily obtained through local authority breakdowns of the result or the constituency boundaries being co-terminous with the local government district.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day of the referendum, Michael Ashcroft conducted a poll of over 2,000 voters to identify the major reasons for their voting choices.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This poll found that among No voters, more than half (57%) stated the pound sterling was one of the most important factors in their decision.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Among Yes voters, the biggest single motivation was "disaffection with Westminster politics".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron admitted he was "very embarrassed" for revealing the Queen's political view, which she had guarded in her own comments.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Alex Salmond, the Scottish First Minister and leader of the SNP, stated that he accepted the "verdict of the people" and called upon "all Scots to follow suit in accepting the democratic verdict of the people of Scotland".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He called the referendum a "triumph for the democratic process and for participation in politics".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He also resigned as SNP leader and as First Minister, saying that "for me as leader my time is nearly over but for Scotland the campaign continues and the dream shall never die".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Northern Ireland's First Minister Peter Robinson and Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones responded positively to the result.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Robinson was "delighted Scotland has voted to remain in the Union".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was a large international reaction to the results of the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The White House congratulated Scotland on their "full and energetic exercise of democracy".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President Barack Obama noted the "debate, discussion, and passionate yet peaceful deliberations" and welcomed the result, saying he looked forward to "continuing our strong and special relationship with all the people of Great Britain and Northern Ireland".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] John Baird, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada, welcomed the decision and praised the conduct of the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Angela Merkel, the Chancellor of Germany, said that, "We [the German government] have always respected the fact that this referendum was called and that the central government in London agreed to this.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] And now we respect the outcome of it as well".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] When asked how she felt about the result she replied "I will not comment on this but just smile".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We look forward to working with all parties across these islands in the years ahead.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Good Friday Agreement of 1998 is the historic template for harmonious and mutually beneficial development of the totality of relationships among the peoples of these islands.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In particular, it has led to a transformation in relationships between the two great traditions on this island".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We have noted that the UK government has extended concrete promises in this regard.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Facing the result of the referendum, Erna Solberg, Prime Minister of Norway, stated to Norwegian broadcaster NRK she was 'glad' Scotland chose to remain in the union and that Scottish independence could have become challenging for Norway as a neighboring country.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Spanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, in a video message, said that the Scottish have avoided serious consequences and "have chosen the most favorable option for everyone; for themselves, for all of Britain, and for the rest of Europe".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Iñigo Urkullu, the President of the Basque Country, stated on the day of the referendum that as the British Government had allowed Scotland to freely decide its own future, the responsibility of the Basque government was to "follow Scotland's footsteps" in securing a similar agreement in Spain.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Artur Mas, President of the Generalitat of Catalonia, described the referendum as a model for a future vote in the Catalonia, and said "What happened in Scotland is not a setback for us, because what we really want in Catalonia is to have the chance to vote".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day after the Scottish referendum, the Catalan parliament voted to hold a "popular consultation" on Catalan independence.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Spanish government said that such a vote would be unconstitutional, but a referendum was held on 9 November 2014 anyway.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The large majority (80%) voted for Catalonia to be an independent country, although two-thirds of Catalans did not participate in the referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Secretary General of NATO Anders Fogh Rasmussen said that he fully-respected "the choice that the people of Scotland have made".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso said the Scottish vote was good for a "united, open, and stronger Europe".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Ten voters discovered that someone had voted under their names at polling stations in Glasgow, a method of fraud termed 'personation', and this led to an investigation by Police Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] During a BBC results broadcast, Scottish Conservative Party leader Ruth Davidson said that "No" campaigners had been "taking tallies" of postal votes and that those showed that the "No" campaign was in the lead.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This resulted in complaints to the electoral commission because the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 stated that people attending proceedings related to the receipt of postal votes must not attempt to ascertain the outcome or "communicate any information" from that voting.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Electoral Commission, who could not investigate criminal allegations, passed the complaints onto Police Scotland.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A formal investigation was subsequently opened, which concluded that there was no criminality.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to official Russian observers, the conditions under which the votes were counted were not up to international standards and that the procedure used made it impossible to check on irregularities.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russia's criticism came just months after the international community had rejected the results of a Kremlin-backed referendum held in the Russian-occupied Ukrainian territory of Crimea.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russian officials said that the strong performance of the Scottish National Party (SNP) at the 2015 general election confirmed their suspicions about the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A petition demanding a second referendum, based on allegations of vote-miscounting, gained more than 70,000 signatures within 24 hours.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In response, Chief Counting Officer Mary Pitcaithly declared that the referendum had been "properly conducted".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An official spokesperson reiterated this point, saying that they were "satisfied that all counts throughout Scotland were properly conducted" and that incidents in the footage could be "easily explained" and were being presented as a "'conspiracy' theory".
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the night of 19 September, hundreds of unionists arrived to celebrate the 'No'-vote and some attacked independence supporters who had gathered in George Square, Glasgow.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Many of the unionists waved Union Jacks or loyalist flags and chanted "Rule, Britannia!" Police officers were drafted in to separate the groups but some unionists broke through police lines.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A number of people were reportedly beaten and bottles were thrown.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A press-photographer told *The Scotsman* he saw people being "kicked about" and was forced to flee after being threatened.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By the end of the following month, the police had made 32 arrests in relation to the events.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The violence was condemned by politicians from both the 'Yes'- and 'No'-camps.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the weeks following the referendum, thousands of people joined the Scottish National Party, the Scottish Greens, or the Scottish Socialist Party, which had all campaigned for a 'Yes'-vote.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The parties claimed that many of the new members were former Scottish Labour Party members.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By 2 October 2014, SNP membership had tripled from 25,000 to 75,000 people, overtaking the Liberal Democrats as the third-largest political party in the UK.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Conservative MP David Mundell said that 80,000 people had signed up to their "Friends of the Union" group during the campaign.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] These people had not necessarily become full members of the Conservative Party because they were not focussed on increasing the number of "card-carrying" members.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, there were calls for greater unity within Scottish unionism and to vote tactically against nationalist candidates.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A grassroots campaign called "Scotland in Union" aimed to encourage tactical voting at the 2015 general election and to publicise the benefits of Scotland being a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Analysis by the Electoral Reform Society prior to the 2015 general election identified some constituencies where tactical voting could succeed, but also pointed out that many voters would find it difficult to support another political party.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Writing after the election, Professor John Curtice said that in only one constituency (Edinburgh South) could it be said that tactical voting succeeded in defeating an SNP candidate.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Two days before the referendum, the leaders of the three main UK political parties publicly pledged to devolve "extensive new powers" to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] They also agreed to a timetable proposed by Gordon Brown.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In his speech responding to the referendum results, David Cameron said that an all-party commission, chaired by Lord Smith of Kelvin, would oversee the implementation of the new powers.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron also called for an answer to the West Lothian question, by removing the right of Scottish MPs to vote on legislation relating only to England.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This proposal was opposed by Gordon Brown, who signed a petition calling for the additional powers to be devolved without any other conditions being attached.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The proposals were debated at length by the UK and Scottish parliaments.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The bill devolving further powers to Scotland was approved unanimously by the Scottish Parliament in March 2016.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, the SNP took a clear lead over the other parties in Scottish opinion polls.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the 2015 general election, the SNP received 1,454,436 votes, 49.97% of the Scottish vote and 56 out of the 59 Scottish seats contested in the election.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Labour lost forty of their forty-one seats and the Liberal Democrats lost ten of their eleven seats – all to the SNP.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The SNP replaced the Liberal Democrats as the third largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] As the Conservatives won an overall majority in the 2015 UK general election, a UK-wide referendum on European Union membership was held in June 2016.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An overall majority of the UK voted to leave the EU (for "Brexit"), while all of Scotland's council areas voted to remain in the EU.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Shortly afterwards, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon announced her intention to prepare legislation for a second independence referendum.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the June 2017 general election, the first major electoral test after the EU referendum, the SNP won 35 of the 59 Scottish seats in the House of Commons.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This represented a drop of 21 seats from 2015, with the Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats all making gains.
[src:portsmouth/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Those results were largely reversed in the December 2019 general election, as the SNP won 48 seats and the Conservatives and Labour both made net losses.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The **2018 United Kingdom local elections** were held on Thursday 3 May 2018, with local council elections taking place in all 32 London boroughs, 34 metropolitan boroughs, 67 district and borough councils and 17 unitary authorities.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] There were also direct elections for the mayoralties of Hackney, Lewisham, Newham, Tower Hamlets and Watford.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] With the exception of those areas that have had boundary changes, the seats up for election were last contested in the 2014 local elections.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] A parliamentary by-election in West Tyrone took place the same day.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Various other local by-elections also took place.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] These numbers are how many seats each party won at the previous comparable election, generally in 2014, rather than which party held the seat on the eve of the election.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Some other news agencies, such as the Press Association, compare against the party holding a seat on the eve of the election, leading to a different analysis of gains and losses.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] There are also 48 Residents Associations' councillors, and 100 'other' / independent councillors.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] All registered electors (British, Irish, Commonwealth and European Union citizens) aged 18 or over on polling day were entitled to vote in the local elections.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] In certain councils, there was a trial system in place where photo ID was required to vote.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] These councils were: Swindon, Gosport, Woking, Bromley, and Watford.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] An estimated 4,000 electors were turned away from polling stations across these trial areas as a result of not having the appropriate form of ID.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The number of councils controlled by each party following the election are shown in the table below.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Both Labour and the Liberal Democrats made modest gains in terms of their respective number of councillors, whereas the Conservatives made a net loss of 35 seats.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] UKIP lost nearly all of the 126 seats they were defending, with only 3 councillors elected.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The following table shows the aggregate results for the 32 councils that were up for election in London.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] †Due to boundary changes, the figures for seat losses/gains are notional changes calculated by the BBC, and do not match up precisely to the London-wide results in 2014.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The following table shows the aggregate results for the 118 councils that were up for election outside of London.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Only four councils switched from a majority for one party to another.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The Conservatives gained Redditch from Labour, and lost control of three councils to the Liberal Democrats: Kingston upon Thames, Richmond upon Thames and South Cambridgeshire.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The Liberal Democrats also gained Three Rivers District Council from no overall control.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Labour gained a majority on three councils that had been under no overall control (Kirklees, Plymouth and Tower Hamlets) while losing their majority on two (Derby and Nuneaton and Bedworth).
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] The Conservatives gained a majority on one council that had been under no overall control (Basildon) while losing their majority on two (Mole Valley and Trafford).
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Labour won the inaugural mayoral election for the Sheffield City Region.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Five other mayoral elections saw no change in the winning party: Labour held four and the Liberal Democrats held one.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] This was the first set of local elections since the 2017 general election.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Most of the seats up for election had last been contested in the 2014 local elections.
[src:portsmouth/2018-united-kingdom-local-elections] Because the group of local councils varies with each cycle of local elections, the BBC and other analysts calculated a projected national vote share, which aims to assess what the council results indicate the UK-wide vote would be if the results were repeated at a general election.
